eft\" |{{lang|zh-Hans|\u6c5f\u9634\u5e02}}\n| align=\"left\" |{{transl|zh|Ji\u0101ngy\u012bn Sh\u00ec}}\n| align=\"right\" |1,594,829\n| align=\"right\" |986.97\n| align=\"right\" |1,615.88\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Yixing|Yixing City]]\n| align=\"left\" |{{lang|zh-Hans|\u5b9c\u5174\u5e02}}\n| align=\"left\" |{{transl|zh|Y\u00edx\u012bng Sh\u00ec}}\n| align=\"right\" |1,235,476\n| align=\"right\" |1,996.61\n| align=\"right\" |618.79\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center; \" |'''Total'''\n| align=\"right\" |'''6,372,624'''\n| align=\"right\" |'''4,627.46'''\n| align=\"right\" |'''1,377.13'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center; \" |Defunct: [[Chong'an District]], [[Nanchang District]], & [[Beitang District]]\n|}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Wuxi-bird-view.PNG|thumb|right|View of Wuxi]]\nWuxi is a regional business hub, with extensive manufacturing and large industrial parks devoted to new industries. Historically a center of textile [[manufacturing]],<ref name=\"EB\"/>  the city has adopted new industries such as [[electric motor]] manufacturing,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cccme.org.cn/shop/cccme2786/index.aspx|title=WUXI HUADA MOTORS CO., LTD.|publisher=CCCME|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902121112/http://www.cccme.org.cn/shop/cccme2786/index.aspx|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hongtaimotor.com/enindex.htm|title=About Us|publisher=Wuxi Hongtai Motor Co.|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902121602/http://www.hongtaimotor.com/enindex.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> MRP [[software development]], bicycle and brake manufacturing, and solar technology, with two major photovoltaic companies, [[Suntech Power]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suntech-power.com/aboutUs.html|title=About Us|publisher=Suntech Power|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902123640/http://www.suntech-power.com/aboutUs.html|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Jetion Holdings Ltd]], based in Wuxi. [[Wuxi Pharma Tech]], a major pharmaceutical company, is based in Wuxi<ref>{{cite book|authors=Arthur Yeung, Katherine Xin, Waldemar Pfoertsch|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ikqPrLXIBMIC&pg=PT44&dq=Wuxi+Jetion+Holdings#v=onepage&q=Wuxi%20Jetion%20Holdings&f=false|title=The Globalization of Chinese Companies: Strategies for Conquering ..|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2011|p=44|isbn = 9780470828816}}</ref> The city has a rapidly developing skyline with the opening of three [[supertall skyscraper]]s in 2014: [[Wuxi IFS]] ({{convert|339|m|sp=us}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/wuxi/the-wharf-times-square-1/356/|title=The Wharf Times Square 1|publisher=CTBUH Skyscraper Center|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902090235/http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/wuxi/the-wharf-times-square-1/356/|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>), [[Wuxi Suning Plaza 1]] ({{convert|328|m|sp=us}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/wuxi-suning-plaza-1/8701|title=Wuxi Suning Plaza 1|publisher=CTBUH Skyscraper Center|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190519111438/http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/wuxi-suning-plaza-1/8701|archive-date=19 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>) and [[Wuxi Maoye City - Marriott Hotel]] ({{convert|303.8|m|sp=us}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/wuxi-maoye-city-marriott-hotel/5287|title=Wuxi Maoye City - Marriott Hotel|publisher=CTBUH Skyscraper Center|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019222032/http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/wuxi-maoye-city-marriott-hotel/5287|archive-date=19 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>).\n\nSince it was established in 1992, [[Wuxi New Area|Wuxi New District]] (WND), covering an area of {{convert|220|km2|sp=us}}, has evolved to be one of the major industrial parks in China. In 2013, it had a GDP of 121.3 billion yuan ($19.54 billion), and an industrial output value of 276.7 billion yuan, accounting for 15% of production in the Wuxi area.\nThe district includes the Wuxi Hi-tech Industrial Development Zone, Wuxi (Taihu) International Technology Park, Wuxi Airport Industrial Park, China (Wuxi) Industrial Expo Park, [[China Wu Culture Expo Park]], and International Education and Living Community.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxinewdistrict/2018-06/05/content_18807750.htm|title=Wuxi New District|newspaper=China Daily|date=5 June 2018|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902130551/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxinewdistrict/2018-06/05/content_18807750.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHotels in Wuxi include Wuxi Maoye City \u2013 Marriott Hotel, [[Hilton Hotel]]'s Wuxi-Lingshan Double Tree Resort near the Lingshan Giant Buddha, [[Kempinski]] Hotel Wuxi, Landison Square Hotel Wuxi, noted for its Wu jade phoenix sculpture in the lobby, [[Radisson Blu]] Resort Wetland Park Wuxi, [[Sheraton Hotels and Resorts|Sheraton]] Wuxi Binhu Hotel and Wuxi Hubin Hotel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/accommodation.html|title=Accomodatations|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012180755/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/accommodation.html|archive-date=12 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Culture and education==\nWuxi is one of the major art and cultural centers of Jiangnan Province. The city is known for its [[Huishan clay figurine]]s, which take their name from the black clay of [[Huishan National Forest Park|Huishan Mountain]]. The figurines have been produced for over 400 years since the [[Ming dynasty]], and are typically large-headed dolls puppies, kittens and chickens.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eNGJDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT293&dq=Wuxi+Huishan+clay+figurines+and+clay+teapots.#v=onepage&q=Wuxi%20Huishan%20clay%20figurines%20and%20clay%20teapots.&f=false|title=Travel Guide of Jiangsu|publisher=DeepLogic|author=Hao, Ni|p=293}}</ref> The figurines are believed to promote longevity and exorcise evil spirits. [[Yixing clay teapot]]s are also of note, made from purple, red and green earth,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=l0orB2AjSHQC&pg=PA44&dq=Wuxi+Huishan+clay+figurines+and+clay+teapots.#v=onepage&q=Wuxi%20Huishan%20clay%20figurines%20and%20clay%20teapots.&f=false|title=Jiangsu|year=2005|isbn=9787508507569}}</ref> which is said to enhance the tea drinking experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=exIcAQAAMAAJ&q=Wuxi+Huishan+clay+figurines+and+clay+teapots.&dq=Wuxi+Huishan+clay+figurines+and+clay+teapots.|title=China's Foreign Trade, Issues 65-74|page=34|year=1981}}</ref>\n\nThe city is served by [[Jiangnan University]], a [[Key national universities|key national university]] of \u201c[[Project 211]]\u201d and center for scientific research, which was originally founded in 1902 and established in 1958 as the Wuxi Institute of Light Industry. In 2001 it was reconstituted by the Ministry of Education with the merger of two other colleges to formally establish Jiangnan University.<ref name=\"uni\">{{cite web|url=http://english.jiangnan.edu.cn/ABOUT_JU/History.htm|title=History|publisher=english.jiangnan.edu.cn|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902144130/http://english.jiangnan.edu.cn/ABOUT_JU/History.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Taihu University of Wuxi]], beside Huishan National Forest Park is a private university and one of the largest in China, covering over 2,000 acres with over 20,000 teachers and students and more than 20 different faculties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://subsites.chinadaily.com.cn/regional/wuxi/2018-04/28/c_223764.htm|title=Taihu University of Wuxi|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902145713/http://subsites.chinadaily.com.cn/regional/wuxi/2018-04/28/c_223764.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:\u7075\u5c71\u5927\u4f5b - panoramio (1).jpg|thumb| [[Grand Buddha at Ling Shan]]]]\nThe city lies in the southern Yangtze River delta on [[Lake Tai]], which is the third largest freshwater lake in China, and a rich resource for tourism in the area with cruises. There are 72 peninsulas and peaks and 48 islets, including [[Yuantouzhu]] (the Islet of Turtlehead) and [[Taihu Xiandao]] (Islands of the Deities).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelchinaguide.com/attraction/jiangsu/wuxi/taihu_lake.htm|title=Taihu Lake|publisher=Travel China Guide|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902132626/https://www.travelchinaguide.com/attraction/jiangsu/wuxi/taihu_lake.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Parks and gardens===\nWuxi has many private gardens or parks built by learned scholars and illustrious people in the past. [[Lihu Park]] in [[Binhu District]] was built in 1927 and named after the politician and economist [[Fan Li]]. The Star of Taihu Lake is noted for its water Ferris wheel. The gardens contains a long embankment with willow trees and a path beside the lake with numerous small bridges and pavilions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/22/content_23809679_2.htm|title=Lihu Lake|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902153506/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/22/content_23809679_2.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On the southwest bank of the lake at the foot of Junzhang Hill is [[Changguangxi Wetland Park]], a {{convert|10|km|sp=us}} stretch of canal connecting Lihu Lake to the north and Taihu Lake to the south. It contains the [[Shitang Bridge]] and a lotus pond.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453168.htm|title=Changguangxi Wetland Park|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902155536/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453168.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Also in Binhu District is [[Wuxi Zoo and Taihu Lake Amusement Park]], an AAAA national landmark with over a 1000 animals including [[Asian elephant]], [[leopard]], [[chimpanzee]], [[giant panda]] and [[white rhinoceros]] and an ecology and science exhibition and recreation area.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453175.htm|title=Wuxi Zoo and Taihu Lake Amusement Park|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902154020/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453175.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe 30 hectare (74 acres) [[Mt. Lingshan Grand Buddha Scenic Area]] on the southwest tip of Wuxi contains the {{Convert|88|m|ft|sp=us}} tall [[Grand Buddha at Ling Shan]], the world's largest bronze Buddha statue. The Mt Lingshan area also contains the Brahma Palace, Xiangfu Temple, Five Mudra Mandala, Nine Dragons Bathing Sakyamuni (a {{convert|7.2|m|sp=us}} statue of [[Sakyamuni]]), and numerous other Buddhist sites.<ref name=\"Mt Lingshan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.travelchinaguide.com/attraction/jiangsu/wuxi/lingshan-buddha.htm|title=Mt. Lingshan Grand Buddha Scenic Area|publisher=Travel China Guide|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902133452/https://www.travelchinaguide.com/attraction/jiangsu/wuxi/lingshan-buddha.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Xihui Park]], established in 1958 at the foot of Xi Shan to the west of the city, contains [[Jichang Garden]]  and the Dragon Light Pagoda.<ref name=\"DK\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QKXACwAAQBAJ&pg=PA222&dq=Xihui+Park+1958+Jichang+Garden+Dragon+Light+Pagoda.#v=onepage&q=Xihui%20Park%201958%20Jichang%20Garden%20Dragon%20Light%20Pagoda.&f=false|title=China|publisher=DK Eyewitness Travel Guides|p=222|year=2016|isbn=9780241279410}}</ref>\n\n===Museums===\n[[Wuxi Museum]] was formally opened on October 1, 2008 following a merger of the Wuxi Revolution Museum, Wuxi Museum and Wuxi Science Museum. Covering over {{convert|71,000|m2|sp=us}} and an exhibition area of {{convert|24,100|m2|sp=us}} it is the largest public cultural building in Wuxi, with 600,000 visitors annually as of 2019. The museum also administers the Chinese National Industry and Commerce Museum of Wuxi, Chengji Art Museum, Zhou Huaimin Painting Museum, Zhang Wentian Former Residence and Wuxi Ancient Stone Inscriptions Museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wxmuseum.com/En/News/Details/EnSummary|title=Introduction of Wuxi Museum|publisher=wxmusuem.com|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190528055956/http://wxmuseum.com/En/News/Details/EnSummary|archive-date=28 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Wuxi Art Museum]], known as the Wuxi Painting and Calligraphy Institute before the rename in 2011, was established on December 7, 1979 in Chong\u2019an district. The current facility has a space of {{convert|1,135|m|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-06/10/content_20958117.htm|title=Wuxi Art Museum (Wuxi Painting and Calligraphy Institute)|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902152607/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-06/10/content_20958117.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Hongshan Archaeological Museum]] in Wuxi New District opened in 2008 and houses artifacts related to the local Wu culture between 770 and 221 BC. The items, which include miniature jade engravings and objects related to burial and musical customs, were unearthed at Hongshan Tomb Complex in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453173.htm|title=Hongshan Archaeological Museum|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902154536/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453173.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Former Residence of Xue Fucheng at No. 152 Xueqian Street in Chong'an district, is the former home of [[Zue Fencheng]], a noted diplomat of the late Qing dynasty and is open to the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453169.htm|title=The Former Residence of Xue Fucheng|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902155106/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453169.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\n[[Wuxi Sports Center]] opened in October 1994 and has a capacity of 30,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/1264239/wuxi-sports-center-wuxi-china|title=Wuxi Sports Center|publisher=Emporis|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902160009/https://www.emporis.com/buildings/1264239/wuxi-sports-center-wuxi-china|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It hosts the Wuxi Classic, a snooker event which attracted the biggest names in snooker. [[Wuxi City Sports Park Stadium]] hosted the 2017 ITTF Asian-Championships (Ping Pong),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ittf.com/tournament/2773/seamaster-2017-ittf-asian-championships/|title=Seamaster 2017 ITTF-Asian Championships - Tournaments|website=International Table Tennis Federation|access-date=24 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624134633/https://www.ittf.com/tournament/2773/seamaster-2017-ittf-asian-championships/|archive-date=24 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[2019 World Cup (snooker)|2019 World Cup]] in snooker in June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=851|title=Beverly World Cup|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723071045/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=851|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Major League Baseball]] based its main Chinese recruitment center in Wuxi since 2009 in Wuxi Development Center at Dongbeitang High School. There Major League Baseball scouts recruit the best players in China in the hopes that they will eventually play professional baseball in America.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thatsmags.com/shanghai/post/16234/tbt-baseball-gets-em-young_1|title=#TBT: Where China Raises Their Future MLB Superstars|publisher=That's Mags|date=24 May 2018|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902165638/https://www.thatsmags.com/shanghai/post/16234/tbt-baseball-gets-em-young_1|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n\nWuxi is situated on the [[Shanghai\u2013Nanjing Intercity High-Speed Railway]], a {{convert|301|km|sp=us}} railway which opened on July 1, 2010, linking it directly with\nthe provincial capital of Nanjing, Shanghai and Suzhou.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelchinaguide.com/china-trains/high-speed/shanghai-nanjing.htm|title=Shanghai to Nanjing Intercity High Speed Train|publisher=Travel China Guide|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902132322/https://www.travelchinaguide.com/china-trains/high-speed/shanghai-nanjing.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Wuxi Metro]] began operations in 2014, with two lines totaling {{convert|19|mi|sp=us}} and over {{convert|124|mi|sp=us}} in total expected with new lines opening over the next few decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelchinaguide.com/cityguides/jiangsu/wuxi/subway/|title=Wuxi Subway|publisher=Travel China Guide|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902132631/https://www.travelchinaguide.com/cityguides/jiangsu/wuxi/subway/|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>[[Sunan Shuofang International Airport]], situated {{Convert|14|km|mi|sp=us}} from the city center, opened in 2004, and has direct flights to [[Beijing]], [[Guangzhou]], [[Shenzhen]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Taipei]], [[Singapore]], and [[Osaka]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelchinaguide.com/cityguides/jiangsu/wuxi/airport.htm|title=Wuxi Sunan Shuofang International Airport|publisher=Travel China Guide|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902132618/https://www.travelchinaguide.com/cityguides/jiangsu/wuxi/airport.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWuxi lies along [[China National Highway 312]] which connects Shanghai to central and northwestern China. The {{convert|274|km|sp=us}} [[Shanghai-Nanjing Expressway]] (G42), which opened in November 1996, connecting it to Shanghai, [[Suzhou]], [[Changzhou]], [[Zhenjiang]] and other cities in Jiangsu province.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/huaqiao/2009-10/10/content_8776758.htm|title=Shanghai-Nanjing Expressway expands with new exit|newspaper=China Daily|date=10 October 2009|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902141347/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/huaqiao/2009-10/10/content_8776758.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The {{convert|62.3|km|sp=us}} [[Wuxi-Yixing Expressway]] connects Wuxi with [[Yixing]] within the regional prefecture-level area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpdi.com.cn/Eng/FM/NewsShowNew.aspx?RID=95E497CD18742679&PID=E38795D34DE9F22A|title=Wuxi-Yixing Expressway, China|publisher=CCCC Highway Consultants Co. Ltd.|accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Ni Zan]], painter (1301\u20131374)\n* [[Xue Fucheng]], diplomat (1838\u20131894)\n*[[Chen Chi]] (1912\u20142005), painter\n* [[Hua Yanjun]] (1893\u20131950), musician\n*[[Liu Tianhua]], folk musician (1895\u20131932)\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[List of twin towns and sister cities in China]]\n* [[China Wu Culture Expo Park]]\n* [[Jiangnan]]\n* [[List of cities in the People's Republic of China by population]]\n\n{{-}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Wuxi}}\n*[http://www.wuxi.gov.cn/ Government website of Wuxi] (available in Chinese, Japanese and English)\n*[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/index.html Wuxi] at ''China Daily''\n{{Jiangsu topics}}\n{{Jiangsu}}\n{{Yangtze River Delta}}\n{{Metropolitan cities of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Regions and cities of China}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Yangtze River Delta]]\n[[Category:Wuxi| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Prefecture-level divisions of Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Jiangnan]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Wu Xi|the footballer|Wu Xi (footballer)|other uses|Wuxi (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                     = {{raise|0.2em|Wuxi}}\n| official_name            = \n| native_name              = {{lower|0.1em|{{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u65e0\u9521\u5e02}}}}}}\n| other_name               = Wusih, Wu Hsi\n| settlement_type          = [[Prefecture-level city]]\n| image_skyline            = Wuxi picture collection.png\n| imagesize                = 250px\n| image_caption            = Clockwise from top: Yunfu Mansion, [[Grand Buddha at Ling Shan]], Lihu Lake, city canal, Liyuan Gardens\n| image_flag               = \n| image_seal               = \n| image_shield             = \n| nickname                 = \n| motto                    = Wuxi is full of warmth and w