 Census\n| population_density_km2   = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| population_metro         = 3,542,319\n| population_density_metro_km2 = \n| population_urban_footnotes     =\n| population_urban               = 3,542,319\n| population_density_urban_km2   =\n| population_density_urban_sq_mi =\n| population_blank1_title  = <!-- Mun. Density rank -->\n| population_blank1        = <!-- ([[List of China administrative regions by population density|4th]]) -->\n| population_blank2_title  = Major [[Nationalities of China|nationalities]]\n| population_note          = \n| population_blank2        = <!-- [[Han Chinese|Han]] - 96%<br />[[Manchu]] - 2%<br />[[Hui people|Hui]] - 2%<br />[[Mongol]]ian - 0.3% -->\n| timezone                 = [[China Standard Time|China Standard]]\n| utc_offset               = +8\n| elevation_footnotes      = <!--for references: use<ref> </ref>  tags-->\n| elevation_m              = \n| postal_code_type         = [[Postal code of China|Postal code]]\n| postal_code              = Urban center: 214000 <br />Other Area: 214200, 214400\n| area_code                = [[Telephone numbers in China|510]]\n|iso_code = [[ISO 3166-2:CN|CN-JS-02]]\n| blank_name               = [[License Plate (China)|License plate prefixes]]\n| blank_info               = {{lang|zh-cn|\u82cfB}}\n| blank1_name              = [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] (2018)\n| blank1_info              = [[Renminbi|CNY]] 1.144 trillion ($172.9 billion)\n| blank2_name              = &nbsp;- per capita\n| blank2_info              = [[Renminbi|CNY]] 174,556 ($26,380)<!-- -->\n| blank3_name              = [[Human Development Index|HDI]]\n| blank3_info              = 0.909 - {{color|#006000|very high}}\n| blank4_name              = [[Chinese language|Local Dialect]]\n| blank4_info              = [[Wu Chinese|Wu]]: [[Wuxi dialect]]\n| website                  = {{URL|www.wuxi.gov.cn}}\n{{collapsed infobox section end}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox Chinese\n| pic     = Wuxi_(Chinese_characters).svg\n| piccap  = \"Wuxi\" in [[Simplified Chinese characters|Simplified]] (top) and [[Traditional Chinese characters|Traditional]] (bottom) Chinese characters\n| picupright = 0.475\n| t       = {{linktext|\u7121\u932b}}\n| s       = {{linktext|\u65e0\u9521}}\n|p=<small>[[People's Republic of China|PRC]] Standard Mandarin:</small><br />W\u00fax\u012b<br /><small>[[Taiwan|ROC]] Standard Mandarin:</small><br />W\u00fax\u00ed|w=<small>[[People's Republic of China|PRC]]:</small> Wu<sup>2</sup>-hsi<sup>1</sup><br /><small>[[Taiwan|ROC]]:</small> Wu<sup>2</sup>-hsi<sup>2</sup>|mi=<small>[[People's Republic of China|PRC]]:</small> {{IPAc-cmn|wu|2|.|x|i|1}}<br /><small>[[Taiwan|ROC]]:</small> {{IPAc-cmn|wu|2|.|x|i|2}}|bpmf=<small>[[People's Republic of China|PRC]]:</small> \u3128\u02ca&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u3112\u3127<br /><small>[[Taiwan|ROC]]:</small> \u3128\u02ca&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u3112\u3127\u02ca\n| wuu     = Vu-sik {{IPA-wuu|vusi\u0294|}}\n| j       = Mou4-sik3\n| y       = M\u00f2uh-sik\n| ci      = {{IPAc-yue|m|ou|4|-|s|ik|3}}\n| poj     = B\u00fb-sek\n| order   = st\n| showflag= p\n}}\n\n'''Wuxi''' ({{zh|s=\u65e0\u9521}}) is a city in southern [[Jiangsu]] province, eastern China, {{convert|135|km|sp=us}} by car to the northwest of downtown [[Shanghai]], between [[Changzhou]] and [[Suzhou]].<ref>{{Google maps | url =https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Shanghai,+China/Wuxi,+Jiangsu,+China/@31.372936,120.6119981,120078m/data=!3m2!1e3!4b1!4m13!4m12!1m5!1m1!1s0x35b27040b1f53c33:0x295129423c364a1!2m2!1d121.473701!2d31.230416!1m5!1m1!1s0x35b38e5843e0a6a5:0xd536ed17c4fd3526!2m2!1d120.31191!2d31.491169?hl=en  | accessdate =2 September 2019}}</ref> In 2017 it had a population of 3,542,319, with 6,553,000 living in the entire prefecture-level city area.\n\nWuxi is a prominent historical and cultural city of China, and has been a thriving economic center since ancient times as a production as an export hub of rice, silk and textiles. In the last few decades it has emerged as a major producer of electrical motors, software, solar technology and bicycle parts. The city lies in the southern delta of the [[Yangtze River]] and on [[Lake Tai]], which with its 48 islets is popular with tourists. Notable landmarks include [[Lihu Park]], the [[Mt. Lingshan Grand Buddha Scenic Area]] and its {{Convert|88|m|ft|sp=us}} tall [[Grand Buddha at Ling Shan]] statue, [[Xihui Park]], [[Wuxi Zoo and Taihu Lake Amusement Park]] and the [[Wuxi Museum]].\n\nThe city is served by [[Sunan Shuofang International Airport]], which opened in 2004, the [[Wuxi Metro]], opened in 2014, and the [[Shanghai\u2013Nanjing Intercity High-Speed Railway]] which connects it to [[Shanghai]]. [[Jiangnan University]], a [[Key national universities|key national university]] of \u201c[[Project 211]]\u201d and center for scientific research, was originally founded in 1902 but was reconstituted in 2001 with the merger of two other colleges.\n\n==Etymology==\nWuxi means \"without tin\" literally. The name \"with tin\" (\u6709\u932b) was once adopted during the short-lived [[Xin Dynasty]]. Despite varied origin stories, many modern Chinese scholars favor the view that the word is derived from the \"[[Yue (state)#Language|old Yue language]]\" or, supposedly, the old [[Kra\u2013Dai languages]].<ref>{{Cite book |script-title=zh:\u65b9\u8a00\u4e0e\u4e2d\u56fd\u6587\u5316|last=Zhou, You|first=Zhenhe, Rujia|publisher=Shanghai People's Publishing House|year=1986|isbn=9787208009653|location=|pages=153\u20134}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=|last=|first=|publisher=Shanghai Cishu Press|year=1996|isbn=7-5326-0299-0|volume=|location=|pages=105|language=zh|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u5386\u53f2\u5927\u8f9e\u5178\u00b7\u5386\u53f2\u5730\u7406\u5377|trans-title=The Great Encyclopaedia of Chinese History, Volume on Historical Geography}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |script-title=zh:\u90d1\u5f20\u5c1a\u82b3\u8bed\u8a00\u5b66\u8bba\u6587\u96c6|last=Zhengzhang|first=Shangfang|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company|year=2012|isbn=9787101061055|location=|pages=|trans-title=Zhengzhang Shangfang's Symposium on Linguistics |script-chapter=zh:\u53e4\u5434\u8d8a\u5730\u540d\u4e2d\u7684\u4f97\u53f0\u8bed\u6210\u5206, \u53e4\u8d8a\u8bed\u5730\u540d\u4eba\u540d\u89e3\u4e49}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe history of Wuxi can be traced back to [[Shang dynasty]] (1600 \u2013 1046 BC).<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|url=http://en.wuxi.gov.cn/a/20130724/364111.shtml|title=History of Wuxi|publisher=Government of Wuxi|accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref>\nThe tin industry thrived in the area in ancient times but it was eventually depleted, so that when Wuxi was established in 202 BCE during the [[Han dynasty]], it was named \"Wuxi\" (Without Tin). Administratively, Wuxi became a district of Biling (later [[Changzhou]]) and only during the [[Yuan dynasty]] (1206\u20131368) did it become an independent prefecture.<ref name=\"EB\">{{cite encyclopedia|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Wuxi|title=Wuxi|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia Britannica|accessdate=2 September 2019|date=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902092607/https://www.britannica.com/place/Wuxi|archivedate=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Wuxi and Changzhou are considered to be the birthplaces of modern industrialization in China.<ref name=\"Shu\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wVC-BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA66&dq=History+Wuxi#v=onepage&q=History%20Wuxi&f=false|title=Entrepreneurship in Family Business: Cases from China|author=Shi, Henry X|publisher=Springer|year=2014|pp=65\u20136|isbn=9783319043043}}</ref>\n\n[[Agriculture]] and the silk industry flourished in Wuxi and the town became a transportation hub under the early Tang Dynasty after the opening of [[Grand Canal (China)|the Grand Canal]] in 609. It became known as one of the biggest markets for rice in China.<ref name=\"EB\"/>\n\nThe [[Donglin Academy]], originally founded during the [[Song dynasty]] (960-1279) was restored in Wuxi in 1604. Not a school, it served as a public forum, advocating a Confucian orthodoxy and ethics. Many of its academicians were retired court officials or officials deposed in the 1590s due to [[Political faction|factionalism]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gDqsCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA686&dq=Donglin+1604+Wuxi#v=onepage&q=Donglin%201604%20Wuxi&f=false|author=Jones, Derek|title=Censorship: A World Encyclopedia|publisher=Routledge|p=686|year=2001|isbn=9781136798641}}</ref>\n\nAs a populous county, its eastern part was separated and resulted in the creation of Jinkui county in 1724. Both Wuxi and Jinkui were utterly devastated by the [[Taiping Rebellion]], which resulted in nearly 2/3 of their population being killed.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Bell, Lynda S.|title=Explaining China's Rural Crisis: Observations From Wuxi County In The Early Twentieth Century|journal = Republican China|volume = 11|pages = 15\u201331|publisher=Republican China, Volume 11, Issue 1|year=1985|doi = 10.1080/08932344.1985.11720078}}</ref> The depleted number of \u201cable-bodied males\u201d (''ding'', {{lang|zh-hant|\u4e01}}) was only of 72,053 and 138,008 individuals in 1865, versus 339,549 and 258,934 in 1830.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u6c5f\u82cf\u7701\u5fd7\u30fb\u4eba\u53e3\u5fd7|last=|first=|publisher=Fangzhi Publishing House|year=|isbn=978-7-801-22526-9|location=|pages=58\u20139|trans-title=Jiangsu Provical Gazetteer, Volume on Demography}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Qing dynasty]] (1636\u20131912), cotton and silk production flourished in Wuxi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YqeyAAAAIAAJ&q=Qing+Wuxi+cotton+silk&dq=Qing+Wuxi+cotton+silk|title=Journal of Women's History - Volume 11 |publisher=Indiana University Press|p=103|year=1999 }}</ref> Trade increased with the opening of ports to Shanghai in 1842,  and [[Zhenjiang]] and [[Nanjing]] in 1858.  Wuxi became a center of the textile industry in China. Textile mills were built in 1894 and silk reeling establishments known as \"filatures\" were built in 1904.<ref name=\"EB\"/> Wuxi was remained the regional center for the waterborne transport of grain. The opening of the railways to Shanghai and to the cities of Zhenjiang and Nanjing to the northwest in 1908 further increased the exports of rice from the area.<ref name=\"EB\"/> Jinkui xian merged into Wuxi County with the onset of the Republic in 1912.<ref name=\"Mass\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YLNwCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT11&dq=jinkui+wuxi+1912#v=onepage&q=jinkui%20wuxi%201912&f=false|title=Yoritomo and the Founding of the First Bakufu|author=Mass, Jeffrey P.|publisher=Stanford University Press|p=11|isbn=9780804780100|date=January 2000}}</ref>\nMany agricultural laborers and merchants moved to [[Shanghai]] in the late 19th century and early 20th century; some prospered in the new factories.<ref name=\"Shu\"/>\n\nAfter World War II, Wuxi's importance as an economic center diminished, but it remains a regional manufacturing hub. Tourism has increasingly become important.<ref name=\"EB\"/> On April 23, 1949, Wuxi was divided into Wuxi City and Wuxi County, and it became a provincial city in 1953 when [[Jiangsu Province]] was founded. In March 1995, several administrative changes were made within Wuxi City and Wuxi County to accommodate for Wuxi New District, with the creation of 19 administrative villages such as Shuofang, Fangqian, Xin\u2019an and Meicun.<ref name=\"history\"/> [[Jiangnan University]] was originally founded in 1902, before merging with two other colleges in 2001 to form the modern university.<ref name=\"uni\"/>\n\n== Administrative divisions ==\nThe [[prefecture-level city]] of Wuxi, [[Jiangsu]], China administers seven [[County-level division|county-level divisions]], including 5 [[District of China|districts]] and 2 [[County-level city|county-level cities]]. The information here presented uses the metric system and data from 2010 Census.\n\nThese districts are sub-divided into 73 [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#Township level|township-level divisions]], including 59 [[Town of China|towns]] and 24 [[Subdistrict|subdistricts]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"6\" |Map\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" |<div class=\"center\" style=\"position: relative\">{{Image label begin|image=Administrative Division Wuxi.png|width={{{1|630}}}|link=}} \n{{Image label|x=940|y=1330|scale={{{1|630}}}/1800|text=''[[Lake Tai]]''}}\n{{Image label|x=420|y=900|scale={{{1|630}}}/1800|text=[[Ge Lake|''Ge<br />Lake'']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1510|y=750|scale={{{1|630}}}/1800|text=[[Xishan District, Wuxi|'''Xishan''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1120|y=700|scale={{{1|630}}}/1800|text=[[Huishan District|'''Huishan''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1220|y=1020|scale={{{1|630}}}/1800|text=[[Binhu District|'''Binhu''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1220|y=810|scale={{{1|630}}}/1800|text=[[Liangxi District|'''Liangxi''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1470|y=970|scale={{{1|630}}}/1800|text=[[Xinwu District, Wuxi|'''Xinwu''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1310|y=400|scale={{{1|630}}}/1800|text=[[Jiangyin|'''Jiangyin<br />{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=340|y=1290|scale={{{1|630}}}/1800|text=[[Yixing|'''Yixing<br />{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n{{Image label end}}</div>\n|-\n! align=\"left\" |Subdivision\n! align=\"left\" |Chinese\n! align=\"left\" |Hanyu Pinyin\n! align=\"left\" |Population {{small|([[Sixth National Population Census of the People's Republic of China|2010]])}}\n! align=\"left\" |Area {{small|(km<sup>2</sup>)}}\n! align=\"left\" |Density {{small|(/km<sup>2</sup>)}}\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center; \" |'''City Proper'''\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Liangxi District]]\n| align=\"left\" |{{lang|zh-Hans|\u6881\u6eaa\u533a}}\n| align=\"left\" |{{transl|zh|Li\u00e1ngx\u012b Q\u016b}}\n| align=\"right\" |944,188\n| align=\"right\" |71.50\n| align=\"right\" |13,205.43\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center; \" |'''Suburban'''\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Xishan District, Wuxi|Xishan District]]\n| align=\"left\" |{{lang|zh-Hans|\u9521\u5c71\u533a}}\n| align=\"left\" |{{transl|zh|X\u012bsh\u0101n Q\u016b}}\n| align=\"right\" |681,300\n| align=\"right\" |399.11\n| align=\"right\" |1,707.05\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Huishan District]]\n| align=\"left\" |{{lang|zh-Hans|\u60e0\u5c71\u533a}}\n| align=\"left\" |{{transl|zh|Hu\u00ecsh\u0101n Q\u016b}}\n| align=\"right\" |691,059\n| align=\"right\" |325.12\n| align=\"right\" |2,125.55\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Binhu District]]\n| align=\"left\" |{{lang|zh-Hans|\u6ee8\u6e56\u533a}}\n| align=\"left\" |{{transl|zh|B\u012bnh\u00fa Q\u016b}}\n| align=\"right\" |688,965\n| align=\"right\" |628.15\n| align=\"right\" |1,096.82\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Xinwu District, Wuxi|Xinwu District]]\n| align=\"left\" |{{lang|zh-Hans|\u65b0\u5434\u533a}}\n| align=\"left\" |{{transl|zh|X\u012bnw\u00fa Q\u016b}}\n| align=\"right\" |536,807\n| align=\"right\" |220.01\n| align=\"right\" |2,439.92\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center; \" |'''Satellite cities ([[County-level city|County-level cities]])'''\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Jiangyin|Jiangyin City]]\n| align=\"left\" |{{lang|zh-Hans|\u6c5f\u9634\u5e02}}\n| align=\"left\" |{{transl|zh|Ji\u0101ngy\u012bn Sh\u00ec}}\n| align=\"right\" |1,594,829\n| align=\"right\" |986.97\n| align=\"right\" |1,615.88\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Yixing|Yixing City]]\n| align=\"left\" |{{lang|zh-Hans|\u5b9c\u5174\u5e02}}\n| align=\"left\" |{{transl|zh|Y\u00edx\u012bng Sh\u00ec}}\n| align=\"right\" |1,235,476\n| align=\"right\" |1,996.61\n| align=\"right\" |618.79\n|- style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center; \" |'''Total'''\n| align=\"right\" |'''6,372,624'''\n| align=\"right\" |'''4,627.46'''\n| align=\"right\" |'''1,377.13'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center; \" |Defunct: [[Chong'an District]], [[Nanchang District]], & [[Beitang District]]\n|}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Wuxi-bird-view.PNG|thumb|right|View of Wuxi]]\nWuxi is a regional business hub, with extensive manufacturing and large industrial parks devoted to new industries. Historically a center of textile [[manufacturing]],<ref name=\"EB\"/>  the city has adopted new industries such as [[electric motor]] manufacturing,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cccme.org.cn/shop/cccme2786/index.aspx|title=WUXI HUADA MOTORS CO., LTD.|publisher=CCCME|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902121112/http://www.cccme.org.cn/shop/cccme2786/index.aspx|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hongtaimotor.com/enindex.htm|title=About Us|publisher=Wuxi Hongtai Motor Co.|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902121602/http://www.hongtaimotor.com/enindex.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> MRP [[software development]], bicycle and brake manufacturing, and solar technology, with two major photovoltaic companies, [[Suntech Power]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suntech-power.com/aboutUs.html|title=About Us|publisher=Suntech Power|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902123640/http://www.suntech-power.com/aboutUs.html|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Jetion Holdings Ltd]], based in Wuxi. [[Wuxi Pharma Tech]], a major pharmaceutical company, is based in Wuxi<ref>{{cite book|authors=Arthur Yeung, Katherine Xin, Waldemar Pfoertsch|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ikqPrLXIBMIC&pg=PT44&dq=Wuxi+Jetion+Holdings#v=onepage&q=Wuxi%20Jetion%20Holdings&f=false|title=The Globalization of Chinese Companies: Strategies for Conquering ..|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2011|p=44|isbn = 9780470828816}}</ref> The city has a rapidly developing skyline with the opening of three [[supertall skyscraper]]s in 2014: [[Wuxi IFS]] ({{convert|339|m|sp=us}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/wuxi/the-wharf-times-square-1/356/|title=The Wharf Times Square 1|publisher=CTBUH Skyscraper Center|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902090235/http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/wuxi/the-wharf-times-square-1/356/|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>), [[Wuxi Suning Plaza 1]] ({{convert|328|m|sp=us}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/wuxi-suning-plaza-1/8701|title=Wuxi Suning Plaza 1|publisher=CTBUH Skyscraper Center|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190519111438/http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/wuxi-suning-plaza-1/8701|archive-date=19 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>) and [[Wuxi Maoye City - Marriott Hotel]] ({{convert|303.8|m|sp=us}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/wuxi-maoye-city-marriott-hotel/5287|title=Wuxi Maoye City - Marriott Hotel|publisher=CTBUH Skyscraper Center|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019222032/http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/wuxi-maoye-city-marriott-hotel/5287|archive-date=19 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>).\n\nSince it was established in 1992, [[Wuxi New Area|Wuxi New District]] (WND), covering an area of {{convert|220|km2|sp=us}}, has evolved to be one of the major industrial parks in China. In 2013, it had a GDP of 121.3 billion yuan ($19.54 billion), and an industrial output value of 276.7 billion yuan, accounting for 15% of production in the Wuxi area.\nThe district includes the Wuxi Hi-tech Industrial Development Zone, Wuxi (Taihu) International Technology Park, Wuxi Airport Industrial Park, China (Wuxi) Industrial Expo Park, [[China Wu Culture Expo Park]], and International Education and Living Community.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxinewdistrict/2018-06/05/content_18807750.htm|title=Wuxi New District|newspaper=China Daily|date=5 June 2018|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902130551/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxinewdistrict/2018-06/05/content_18807750.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHotels in Wuxi include Wuxi Maoye City \u2013 Marriott Hotel, [[Hilton Hotel]]'s Wuxi-Lingshan Double Tree Resort near the Lingshan Giant Buddha, [[Kempinski]] Hotel Wuxi, Landison Square Hotel Wuxi, noted for its Wu jade phoenix sculpture in the lobby, [[Radisson Blu]] Resort Wetland Park Wuxi, [[Sheraton Hotels and Resorts|Sheraton]] Wuxi Binhu Hotel and Wuxi Hubin Hotel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/accommodation.html|title=Accomodatations|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012180755/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/accommodation.html|archive-date=12 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Culture and education==\nWuxi is one of the major art and cultural centers of Jiangnan Province. The city is known for its [[Huishan clay figurine]]s, which take their name from the black clay of [[Huishan National Forest Park|Huishan Mountain]]. The figurines have been produced for over 400 years since the [[Ming dynasty]], and are typically large-headed dolls puppies, kittens and chickens.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eNGJDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT293&dq=Wuxi+Huishan+clay+figurines+and+clay+teapots.#v=onepage&q=Wuxi%20Huishan%20clay%20figurines%20and%20clay%20teapots.&f=false|title=Travel Guide of Jiangsu|publisher=DeepLogic|author=Hao, Ni|p=293}}</ref> The figurines are believed to promote longevity and exorcise evil spirits. [[Yixing clay teapot]]s are also of note, made from purple, red and green earth,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=l0orB2AjSHQC&pg=PA44&dq=Wuxi+Huishan+clay+figurines+and+clay+teapots.#v=onepage&q=Wuxi%20Huishan%20clay%20figurines%20and%20clay%20teapots.&f=false|title=Jiangsu|year=2005|isbn=9787508507569}}</ref> which is said to enhance the tea drinking experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=exIcAQAAMAAJ&q=Wuxi+Huishan+clay+figurines+and+clay+teapots.&dq=Wuxi+Huishan+clay+figurines+and+clay+teapots.|title=China's Foreign Trade, Issues 65-74|page=34|year=1981}}</ref>\n\nThe city is served by [[Jiangnan University]], a [[Key national universities|key national university]] of \u201c[[Project 211]]\u201d and center for scientific research, which was originally founded in 1902 and established in 1958 as the Wuxi Institute of Light Industry. In 2001 it was reconstituted by the Ministry of Education with the merger of two other colleges to formally establish Jiangnan University.<ref name=\"uni\">{{cite web|url=http://english.jiangnan.edu.cn/ABOUT_JU/History.htm|title=History|publisher=english.jiangnan.edu.cn|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902144130/http://english.jiangnan.edu.cn/ABOUT_JU/History.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Taihu University of Wuxi]], beside Huishan National Forest Park is a private university and one of the largest in China, covering over 2,000 acres with over 20,000 teachers and students and more than 20 different faculties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://subsites.chinadaily.com.cn/regional/wuxi/2018-04/28/c_223764.htm|title=Taihu University of Wuxi|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902145713/http://subsites.chinadaily.com.cn/regional/wuxi/2018-04/28/c_223764.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:\u7075\u5c71\u5927\u4f5b - panoramio (1).jpg|thumb| [[Grand Buddha at Ling Shan]]]]\nThe city lies in the southern Yangtze River delta on [[Lake Tai]], which is the third largest freshwater lake in China, and a rich resource for tourism in the area with cruises. There are 72 peninsulas and peaks and 48 islets, including [[Yuantouzhu]] (the Islet of Turtlehead) and [[Taihu Xiandao]] (Islands of the Deities).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelchinaguide.com/attraction/jiangsu/wuxi/taihu_lake.htm|title=Taihu Lake|publisher=Travel China Guide|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902132626/https://www.travelchinaguide.com/attraction/jiangsu/wuxi/taihu_lake.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Parks and gardens===\nWuxi has many private gardens or parks built by learned scholars and illustrious people in the past. [[Lihu Park]] in [[Binhu District]] was built in 1927 and named after the politician and economist [[Fan Li]]. The Star of Taihu Lake is noted for its water Ferris wheel. The gardens contains a long embankment with willow trees and a path beside the lake with numerous small bridges and pavilions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/22/content_23809679_2.htm|title=Lihu Lake|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902153506/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/22/content_23809679_2.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On the southwest bank of the lake at the foot of Junzhang Hill is [[Changguangxi Wetland Park]], a {{convert|10|km|sp=us}} stretch of canal connecting Lihu Lake to the north and Taihu Lake to the south. It contains the [[Shitang Bridge]] and a lotus pond.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453168.htm|title=Changguangxi Wetland Park|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902155536/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453168.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Also in Binhu District is [[Wuxi Zoo and Taihu Lake Amusement Park]], an AAAA national landmark with over a 1000 animals including [[Asian elephant]], [[leopard]], [[chimpanzee]], [[giant panda]] and [[white rhinoceros]] and an ecology and science exhibition and recreation area.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453175.htm|title=Wuxi Zoo and Taihu Lake Amusement Park|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902154020/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453175.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe 30 hectare (74 acres) [[Mt. Lingshan Grand Buddha Scenic Area]] on the southwest tip of Wuxi contains the {{Convert|88|m|ft|sp=us}} tall [[Grand Buddha at Ling Shan]], the world\u2019s largest bronze Buddha statue. The Mt Lingshan area also contains the Brahma Palace, Xiangfu Temple, Five Mudra Mandala, Nine Dragons Bathing Sakyamuni (a {{convert|7.2|m|sp=us}} statue of [[Sakyamuni]]), and numerous other Buddhist sites.<ref name=\"Mt Lingshan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.travelchinaguide.com/attraction/jiangsu/wuxi/lingshan-buddha.htm|title=Mt. Lingshan Grand Buddha Scenic Area|publisher=Travel China Guide|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902133452/https://www.travelchinaguide.com/attraction/jiangsu/wuxi/lingshan-buddha.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Xihui Park]], established in 1958 at the foot of Xi Shan to the west of the city, contains [[Jichang Garden]]  and the Dragon Light Pagoda.<ref name=\"DK\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QKXACwAAQBAJ&pg=PA222&dq=Xihui+Park+1958+Jichang+Garden+Dragon+Light+Pagoda.#v=onepage&q=Xihui%20Park%201958%20Jichang%20Garden%20Dragon%20Light%20Pagoda.&f=false|title=China|publisher=DK Eyewitness Travel Guides|p=222|year=2016|isbn=9780241279410}}</ref>\n\n===Museums===\n[[Wuxi Museum]] was formally opened on October 1, 2008 following a merger of the Wuxi Revolution Museum, Wuxi Museum and Wuxi Science Museum. Covering over {{convert|71,000|m2|sp=us}} and an exhibition area of {{convert|24,100|m2|sp=us}} it is the largest public cultural building in Wuxi, with 600,000 visitors annually as of 2019. The museum also administers the Chinese National Industry and Commerce Museum of Wuxi, Chengji Art Museum, Zhou Huaimin Painting Museum, Zhang Wentian Former Residence and Wuxi Ancient Stone Inscriptions Museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wxmuseum.com/En/News/Details/EnSummary|title=Introduction of Wuxi Museum|publisher=wxmusuem.com|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190528055956/http://wxmuseum.com/En/News/Details/EnSummary|archive-date=28 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Wuxi Art Museum]], known as the Wuxi Painting and Calligraphy Institute before the rename in 2011, was established on December 7, 1979 in Chong\u2019an district. The current facility has a space of {{convert|1,135|m|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-06/10/content_20958117.htm|title=Wuxi Art Museum (Wuxi Painting and Calligraphy Institute)|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902152607/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-06/10/content_20958117.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Hongshan Archaeological Museum]] in Wuxi New District opened in 2008 and houses artifacts related to the local Wu culture between 770 and 221 BC. The items, which include miniature jade engravings and objects related to burial and musical customs, were unearthed at Hongshan Tomb Complex in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453173.htm|title=Hongshan Archaeological Museum|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902154536/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453173.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Former Residence of Xue Fucheng at No. 152 Xueqian Street in Chong'an district, is the former home of [[Zue Fencheng]], a noted diplomat of the late Qing dynasty and is open to the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453169.htm|title=The Former Residence of Xue Fucheng|newspaper=China Daily|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902155106/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/2015-01/30/content_19453169.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\n[[Wuxi Sports Center]] opened in October 1994 and has a capacity of 30,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/1264239/wuxi-sports-center-wuxi-china|title=Wuxi Sports Center|publisher=Emporis|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902160009/https://www.emporis.com/buildings/1264239/wuxi-sports-center-wuxi-china|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It hosts the Wuxi Classic, a snooker event which attracted the biggest names in snooker. [[Wuxi City Sports Park Stadium]] hosted the 2017 ITTF Asian-Championships (Ping Pong),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ittf.com/tournament/2773/seamaster-2017-ittf-asian-championships/|title=Seamaster 2017 ITTF-Asian Championships - Tournaments|website=International Table Tennis Federation|access-date=24 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624134633/https://www.ittf.com/tournament/2773/seamaster-2017-ittf-asian-championships/|archive-date=24 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[2019 World Cup (snooker)|2019 World Cup]] in snooker in June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=851|title=Beverly World Cup|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723071045/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=851|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Major League Baseball]] based its main Chinese recruitment center in Wuxi since 2009 in Wuxi Development Center at Dongbeitang High School. There Major League Baseball scouts recruit the best players in China in the hopes that they will eventually play professional baseball in America.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thatsmags.com/shanghai/post/16234/tbt-baseball-gets-em-young_1|title=#TBT: Where China Raises Their Future MLB Superstars|publisher=That's Mags|date=24 May 2018|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902165638/https://www.thatsmags.com/shanghai/post/16234/tbt-baseball-gets-em-young_1|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n\nWuxi is situated on the [[Shanghai\u2013Nanjing Intercity High-Speed Railway]], a {{convert|301|km|sp=us}} railway which opened on July 1, 2010, linking it directly with\nthe provincial capital of Nanjing, Shanghai and Suzhou.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelchinaguide.com/china-trains/high-speed/shanghai-nanjing.htm|title=Shanghai to Nanjing Intercity High Speed Train|publisher=Travel China Guide|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902132322/https://www.travelchinaguide.com/china-trains/high-speed/shanghai-nanjing.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Wuxi Metro]] began operations in 2014, with two lines totaling {{convert|19|mi|sp=us}} and over {{convert|124|mi|sp=us}} in total expected with new lines opening over the next few decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelchinaguide.com/cityguides/jiangsu/wuxi/subway/|title=Wuxi Subway|publisher=Travel China Guide|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902132631/https://www.travelchinaguide.com/cityguides/jiangsu/wuxi/subway/|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>[[Sunan Shuofang International Airport]], situated {{Convert|14|km|mi|sp=us}} from the city center, opened in 2004, and has direct flights to [[Beijing]], [[Guangzhou]], [[Shenzhen]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Taipei]], [[Singapore]], and [[Osaka]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelchinaguide.com/cityguides/jiangsu/wuxi/airport.htm|title=Wuxi Sunan Shuofang International Airport|publisher=Travel China Guide|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902132618/https://www.travelchinaguide.com/cityguides/jiangsu/wuxi/airport.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWuxi lies along [[China National Highway 312]] which connects Shanghai to central and northwestern China. The {{convert|274|km|sp=us}} [[Shanghai-Nanjing Expressway]] (G42), which opened in November 1996, connecting it to Shanghai, [[Suzhou]], [[Changzhou]], [[Zhenjiang]] and other cities in Jiangsu province.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/huaqiao/2009-10/10/content_8776758.htm|title=Shanghai-Nanjing Expressway expands with new exit|newspaper=China Daily|date=10 October 2009|accessdate=2 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902141347/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/huaqiao/2009-10/10/content_8776758.htm|archive-date=2 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The {{convert|62.3|km|sp=us}} [[Wuxi-Yixing Expressway]] connects Wuxi with [[Yixing]] within the regional prefecture-level area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpdi.com.cn/Eng/FM/NewsShowNew.aspx?RID=95E497CD18742679&PID=E38795D34DE9F22A|title=Wuxi-Yixing Expressway, China|publisher=CCCC Highway Consultants Co. Ltd.|accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Ni Zan]], painter (1301\u20131374)\n* [[Xue Fucheng]], diplomat (1838\u20131894)\n*[[Chen Chi]] (1912\u20142005), painter\n* [[Hua Yanjun]] (1893\u20131950), musician\n*[[Liu Tianhua]], folk musician (1895\u20131932)\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[List of twin towns and sister cities in China]]\n* [[China Wu Culture Expo Park]]\n* [[Jiangnan]]\n* [[List of cities in the People's Republic of China by population]]\n\n{{-}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Wuxi}}\n*[http://www.wuxi.gov.cn/ Government website of Wuxi] (available in Chinese, Japanese and English)\n*[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/jiangsu/wuxi/index.html Wuxi] at ''China Daily''\n{{Jiangsu topics}}\n{{Jiangsu}}\n{{Yangtze River Delta}}\n{{Metropolitan cities of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Regions and cities of China}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Yangtze River Delta]]\n[[Category:Wuxi| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Prefecture-level divisions of Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Jiangnan]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParks and gardens:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wuxi"}
{"title_page": "Rajith Kumar", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Rajith Kumar\n| image         = Rajith Kumar.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Rajith in 2016\n| birth_name    = Rajith Kumar R.\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = [[Attingal]], [[Thiruvananthapuram district|Trivandrum<!--Thiruvananthapuram was known as Trivandrum until 1991-->]], [[Kerala]], India\n| other_names   = Dr. Rajith Kumar, DRK\n| occupation    = {{hlist|Public speaker|Lecturer|Educational counselor|Writer|Philanthropist}}\n| years_active  = 1996 \u2013 present (Lecturing)\n| spouse        = \n}}\n'''Rajith Kumar R.'''  is an Indian [[public speaker]], lecturer, [[School counselor|educational counselor]], writer, and [[philanthropist]] from [[Kerala]]. He works as a lecturer in the Botany department of [[Sree Sankara College]], [[Kalady]].<!--Per WP:TAGBOMBING, adding unnecessary tags counts as vandalism. Lead is a summary of body and does not require citation. Content is already cited in the body.--> He has authored more than ten books, related to self-improvement and religious texts. Some of his statements made in public speeches has been the subject of controversy. Rajith is an active humanitarian worker, he founded the \"Dr. Rajith Charitable Services\" and is a life-member of [[Indian Red Cross Society]].\n\nRajith holds a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (Ph.D.) in [[microbiology]] and [[Master of Philosophy]] (M. Phil) in [[cytogenetics]].<!--Per WP:TAGBOMBING, adding unnecessary tags counts as vandalism. Lead is a summary of body and does not require citation. Content is already cited in the body.--> He has received several awards and honours, including the Samoohya Saksharatha Prathibha award from Kerala State Literacy Mission Authority, [[Government of Kerala]]. In 2020, Rajith contested in the [[Bigg Boss (Malayalam season 2)|second season]] of Malayalam [[reality TV]] show ''[[Bigg Boss (Malayalam TV series)|Bigg Boss]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nRajith Kumar hails from Kizhuvilam, [[Attingal]] in [[Thiruvananthapuram district]] of [[Kerala]], India. His father died before he was born, his mother was a last grade government employee in the health department. He had his schooling from Government Model Boys Higher Secondary School, Attingal. Rajith was adjudged Best Student while studying at [[Mar Ivanios College]] in Thiruvananthapuram, from where he graduated with a bachelor's degree ([[Bachelor of Science|B.Sc]]) in [[botany]] and had his master's degree ([[Master of Science|M.Sc]]) from [[N. S. S. College, Pandalam]] with first rank.<ref name=\"TH-article\">{{cite news|last=Pradeep|first=K.|title=Teaching from the heart|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/Teaching-from-the-heart/article16369919.ece|accessdate=1 February 2020|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=5 November 2009}}</ref> He then took a [[Master of Philosophy]] (M. Phil) in [[cytogenetics]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (Ph.D) in [[microbiology]] (passed with [[gold medal]]<ref name=\"TNIE-article\"/>). He also went on to take a [[Bachelor of Education]] (B.Ed) degree in [[natural science]], a bachelor's degree in [[library and information science]] (BLIS), a master's degree (M.S) in [[psychotherapy]], and a diploma in [[Vedanta]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.asianetnews.com/biggboss/bigg-boss-malayalam-season-two-contestant-rajith-kumar-q3n3k1|title=\u0d05\u0d24\u0d46 \u0d07\u0d24\u0d4d \u0d30\u0d1c\u0d3f\u0d24\u0d4d \u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d \u0d24\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d46! \u0d2c\u0d3f\u0d17\u0d4d \u0d2c\u0d4b\u0d38\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d \u0d0e\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d41\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d24\u0d4d \u0d35\u0d28\u0d4d\u200d \u0d2e\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d35\u0d31\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d4d\u200d|work=[[Asianet News]]|language=ml|author=Web desk|date=5 January 2020|accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dr.Rajith Kumar in Janakeiya Kodathi {{!}} Dr.\u0d30\u0d1c\u0d3f\u0d24\u0d4d \u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d7c \u0d1c\u0d28\u0d15\u0d40\u0d2f \u0d15\u0d4b\u0d1f\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d4d\u200d {{!}} Ep# 13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HWpyLcjk6Tw|publisher=24 News|accessdate=21 January 2020|language=ml|date=3 March 2019}}</ref> He has also passed the [[UGC NET]] examination.<ref name=\"TNIE-article\"/>\n\n==Work==\nIn 1996, he joined as a lecturer in Botany department at [[Sree Sankara College]], [[Kalady]] and continued there until 2003. Since his mother refused to leave his hometown [[Attingal]] to stay with him, he took a transfer to Government Model Boys Higher Secondary School, Attingal (where he studied) to a lower position as a teacher even after receiving a doctorate. But later he was transferred back to Sree Sankara College and visited mother at weekends. In 2009, the [[Thiruvananthapuram district]] panchayat nominated and selected him as a member of its Working Group. In September 2009, the [[Chirayinkeezhu]] panchayat and Kerala State Literacy Mission Authority honoured him with Samoohya Saksharatha Prathibha award.<ref name=\"TH-article\"/> He convened \"Keralagramam\", an [[Indian Science Congress Association]] programme held in Thiruvananthapuram in 2010.<ref name=\"TNIE-article\"/>\n\nRajith is an active humanitarian worker, he founded the Dr. Rajith Charitable Services and is a life-member of [[Indian Red Cross Society]]. From 2000s, he has been offering free coaching classes, counselling sessions, uniforms, textbooks, medicine, food among other things to economically backward students, funded from his own salary. By 2009, number of such students he gave assistance surpassed 25,000. Rajith has taken part in training programmes conducted by [[National Council of Educational Research and Training|NCERT]] and [[State Council of Educational Research and Training, Kerala|SCERT]] in adolescent education.<ref name=\"TNIE-article\">{{cite news|last=Prakash|first=Asha|title=The power of one|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/thiruvananthapuram/2009/dec/08/the-power-of-one-111052.html|accessdate=1 February 2020|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=8 December 2009}}</ref> He is also known for his public awareness speeches. He has authored more than ten books in [[Malayalam]], related to religion and personal motivation.\n\nHe appeared in the children's [[feature film]] ''Manalchithrangal'' (2015). In 2018, he appeared in the short film ''Daivathinte Naadu'', and in a music video, ''Amma'', in the following year. In 2020, he entered the Bigg Boss house as a contestant in the [[reality television]] show [[Bigg Boss (Malayalam season 2)|''Bigg Boss'' (Malayalam season 2)]] on [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/bigg-boss-malayalam-2-contestant-dr-rajith-kumar-everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-controversial-public-speaker/articleshow/73111049.cms|title=Bigg Boss Malayalam 2 contestant Dr Rajith Kumar: Everything you need to know about the controversial public speaker|work=The Times of India|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> When he was ousted from the show, his supporters organized a public gathering to welcome him at [[Cochin International Airport]]. The gathering was organized despite the government's cautionary measures against the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kerala|coronavirus pandemic]]. Rajith and 79 other people involved in the gathering were booked by the police for flouting government advisory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 79 Booked for Organising Mass Reception for Bigg Boss Malayalam 2 Contestant Rajith Kumar |url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/coronavirus-79-booked-for-organising-mass-reception-for-bigg-boss-malayalam-2-contestant-rajith-kumar-2538089.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=News18 |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Rajith Kumar, 11 others taken into custody by Kerala police for flouting COVID-19 advisory |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/2020/mar/17/rajith-kumar-taken-into-custody-by-kerala-police-for-flouting-covid-19-advisory-2117809.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The New Indian Express}}</ref> He was released on bail after questioning.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bigg Boss Malayalam 2's Rajith Kumar, arrested over unlawful assembly, granted bail|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/bigg-boss-malayalam-2s-rajith-kumar-arrested-over-unlawful-assembly-granted-bail/articleshow/74684593.cms|accessdate=19 March 2020|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==In the media==\nIn 2013, while speaking at [[Government College for Women, Thiruvananthapuram]] at the \"moral education\" campaign organised by the [[Department of General and Higher Education (Kerala)|Department of General and Higher Education]], he criticised women's current dressing style. It received media attention after a student protested by booing and boycotting the speech. [[Shobhana George]] complained against his statement in the [[Kerala State Human Rights Commission]] which asked the Collegiate Education Department to enquire into the matter. [[Deputy Director]] Girija Devi who conducted the enquiry reported that Kumar's speech was \"a piece of art and the opposition by a graduate student to the speech was an immature response\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Now, Rajith Kumar's misogyny becomes 'art'|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/thiruvananthapuram/Now-Rajith-Kumars-misogyny-becomes-art/articleshow/20596003.cms|accessdate=2 October 2019|date=15 June 2013|work=[[The Times of India]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, in a counselling session held in [[Kasaragod]] he reportedly stated that women who wear [[jeans]] can give birth to [[transgender]] children and the children born to rebel men and women is found to be [[Autism|autistic]], claiming to have scientific backing. He received rebuke, with media and public calling it ill-informed, unscientific, and offensive. Kumar defended it saying that there are efforts to put him in bad light and only a certain portion from his 4-hour long speech was taken and is used to create misunderstanding among people. He reiterated and defended his statements again in the show ''Njangalkum Parayanund'' in [[Mathrubhumi News]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Varier |first1=Megha |title='Wearing jeans leads to birth of trans kids': Kerala Prof slammed for offensive remarks |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/wearing-jeans-leads-birth-trans-kids-kerala-prof-slammed-offensive-remark-78960 |accessdate=2 October 2019|work=[[The News Minute]]|date=3 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Women who dress like men, wear jeans give birth to transgenders: Kerala professor|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/040418/women-who-dress-like-men-give-birth-to-transkids-kerala-professor.html|accessdate=2 October 2019|date=4 April 2018|work=[[Deccan Chronicle]]}}</ref> Following that, health minister [[K. K. Shailaja]] released a press note barring Kumar from speaking in government programmes, citing that he spreads superstition and social discord.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/state-to-initiate-action-against-counsellor/article23415500.ece|title=State to initiate action against counsellor|date=2 April 2018|work=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=3 April 2018|author=Special correspondent|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Although his statements has received criticism, he has also found support from a section of public.<ref>{{cite web|last=Raja|first=Vidya|title='Women in Jeans' Give Birth to Trans Kids. Really? and You Claim to Be a Botany Lecturer|url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/136946/rajith-kumar-ridiculous-statements-women-jeans-kerala/|accessdate=2 October 2019|date=6 April 2018|publisher=[[The Better India]]}}</ref> Following the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kerala]], he said that he had a 'pure heart' and therefore he cannot be infected with coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rajith Kumar fans' airport gathering exposes Kerala's coronavirus preventive system |url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/news/kerala/2020/03/16/bigg-boss-rajith-kumar-fans-gathering-intelligence-failure-corona-scare.html |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=OnManorama |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Thiricharivu: The Power of Discrimination''<ref>{{cite web|title=Thiricharivu: The Power of Discrimination|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/s960x960/1669853_464073380387130_973326160_o.jpg?_nc_cat=105&_nc_oc=AQmWiW0WLG9wdrRa7PQxXvZubjuV1gXmzxVriBrdmw3frAh6MTOAKOVfOwqN31n1R_sC8GhkPWj-vCfImZb1sZD7&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=0f2fddda4f18f046abd7860d76956a4a&oe=5ECFC045|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Enne Vismayipicha Quran Sookthangal''<ref>{{cite web|title=Enne Vismayipicha Quran Sookthangal|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/s960x960/20989207_1277625682365225_6944141026383949430_o.jpg?_nc_cat=106&_nc_oc=AQmIeJtHzBKCEcLRob4-4Fk79BG_PCoZ2ceRLkx7NWD7yxYcOyduJYPEI4pZTPnStLHzm2QnR3XxRwmw1x6Znicx&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=10978df51bb0bdcbae5fd3dba58550b7&oe=5EC2A2BF|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Srimad Bhagavad Gita Sandhesham''\n* ''Ennil Karunaniracha Bible''<ref>{{cite web|title=Ennil Karunaniracha Bible|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/s960x960/25627047_1424355261025599_9019249648867682904_o.jpg?_nc_cat=107&_nc_ohc=zkKIZjh0MP8AX8GsB10&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=c6c1cfab63ecc3ec25a61da13b868577&oe=5EBF573E|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Unaru Unaru''<ref>{{cite web|title=Unaru Unaru|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/s960x960/12513483_800966413364490_5972552697250588791_o.jpg?_nc_cat=109&_nc_oc=AQk1VQUHiXi7UNhzYRg7U-p6YF8zw4U4UG-QvOF2ipen1xd6AKhIF2Q2JkOJ5BLcEOCaOykYD9kwPQHAqjnfwIr4&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=a9efea14d08804884bad97e80a328d9a&oe=5ECC3182|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Jeevitha Vijayathileku 22 Padikal: Steps to Success''<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeevitha Vijayathileku 22 Padikal: Steps to Success|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/12510453_800966326697832_263336001316150501_n.jpg?_nc_cat=110&_nc_oc=AQkiEJBUdrdwI7qa34bU9bzWd5ufpsOPOpI9zPorxLzjqVpaLQyr6f2raw1RK3JQbI_jKAtQDVTy1XRa-nyJQbon&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=2bb5efd28d3ebed40cf11e83ec9e1dc7&oe=5ED31610|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Gita Mahathvam: Bhagavat Gitayile Shasthra Sathyangal''<ref>{{cite web|title=Gita Mahathvam: Bhagavat Gitayile Shasthra Sathyangal|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/11800284_723695841091548_5439407470196916508_n.jpg?_nc_cat=107&_nc_oc=AQkJ7JSenGd1SoWX8BR8SBzxYQuCLpUTor3HRUvtamEAKQveGdG_LnVG5CgF2_zqOMMA2xavzDnL8EhFeiXr5j8I&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=c0f78223ada655c66c2b99af5cd267e3&oe=5EC31DC5|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Ramayanam''<ref>{{cite web|title=Ramayanam|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/p720x720/27355539_1424353974359061_2567456907614370402_o.jpg?_nc_cat=103&_nc_oc=AQn_o5A7sM8R5dZr2p3Z_i91-RRjW_OiDEb_N0ccyroSKw7u_HI7YnG1CkNk323lsRQehpW1SwJzvmVlNzVYodja&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&_nc_tp=6&oh=d3277366fa2ed558cd2509606a080a3d&oe=5EC025EB|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Enne Njaniyakkunna Bhagavat Gita''<ref>{{cite web|title=Enne Njaniyakkunna Bhagavat Gita|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/s960x960/14231382_943161439144986_3063133532158152889_o.jpg?_nc_cat=102&_nc_oc=AQl5gfp4X8OYYWOmvpp8hgdDsfo2SXfPZoaX55rkXS9UlG7UAwjn8glVUZM0uNnaJCCft8lHYsXC-17nWefeInFo&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=949d89d3cf40a6b948fe846556d7249a&oe=5ED2A9A1|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Shri Mahabhagavata Rahasyam''<ref>{{cite web|title=Shri Mahabhagavata Rahasyam|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/s960x960/35439687_1574197732708017_1195864486007799808_o.jpg?_nc_cat=109&_nc_ohc=M0Pdzhi4p2oAX9lA2vh&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=f14867f5256eda13f2742c60577ca53f&oe=5ED056AB|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Mahabharatacharitham: Ithihasa Rahasyangal''<ref>{{cite web|title=Mahabharatacharitham: Ithihasa Rahasyangal|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/s960x960/69298192_2241048376022946_4786516729545097216_o.jpg?_nc_cat=105&_nc_oc=AQlxI2zl71u_BQUW05yokjsXvtmFoTCWEtlG5H5BMyF2HfsVCavDncHwUcGO3dq2LltnpHmnWqA9acjpR07psOPd&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=94957f65a5f56f369a5e608df29acb49&oe=5E8E2998|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Manthrikumaran]]''\n| Actor\n| Directed by Thulasidas\n|-\n|-\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''News Hour''\n| Interviewee\n| [[Asianet News]]\n|-\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Ente Daivam''\n| Interviewee\n| [[Asianet Cable Vision|ACV]] interview by [[Rahul Easwar]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Manalchithrangal''\n| Actor\n| [[Feature film]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Kumar|first=Rajith|title=Manalchithrangal|url=https://www.facebook.com/Dr.Rajith/photos/a.463659133761888/661855107275622/?type=3&theater |website=[[Facebook]]|publisher=Dr.Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| \n| ''Selfie''\n| Participant\n| [[Kairali TV]] moderated by Sreedhanya\n|-\n| \n| ''Nammal Thammil''\n| Participant\n| [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]] \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Njangalkum Parayanund''\n| Guest and subject\n| Episode 252, [[Mathrubhumi News]] talk show<ref>{{cite web|title=Controversial Comment On Autism: Who Will Bell The Cat? Njangalkum Parayanund, Ep:252|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aErD-QEWXZs|publisher=[[Mathrubhumi News]]|accessdate=30 January 2020|website=[[YouTube]]|language=ml|date=25 March 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Daivathinte Naadu''\n| Actor\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Janakeiya Kodathi''\n| Interviewee\n| Episode 13, [[Twentyfour News]] interview by Arun Kumar\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Amma''\n| Actor\n| Music video\n|-\n| 2020\n| [[Bigg Boss (Malayalam season 2)|''Bigg Boss'' (Malayalam season 2)]]\n| Contestant\n| [[Reality TV]] show on [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]], 70 episodes\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n* 2009: Samoohya Saksharatha Prathibha from [[Chirayinkeezhu]] panchayat and Kerala State Literacy Mission Authority.<ref name=\"TH-article\"/>\n* 2010: Rashtra Sevana Prathibha Puraskar from Global Confederation of Pravasee Malayalees<ref>{{cite web |title=Rastra Sevana Prathibha Puraskar |url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/528097_471714842882319_586567152_n.jpg?_nc_cat=107&_nc_ohc=03CKkxPRoO0AX8CFzHq&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=f0dbca187bb25dfb0757be677703e494&oe=5E65DFD0|accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=2013}}</ref>\n* 2017: Dr. Ambedkar Excellency Service National Award from Bharatiya Dalit Sahitya Akademi<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. Ambedkar Excellency National Award for Dr. Rajith Kumar|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/s960x960/18921051_1207842669343527_4715951604494761086_o.jpg?_nc_cat=106&_nc_ohc=Bv4urAcvWDsAX89qJkj&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&_nc_tp=1&oh=6deb3c0f16463582bc2d1dcc2f581d55&oe=5E92CEFB|accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=2018}}</ref>\n* 2017: Samoohya Sevana Rathnam from Kerala Urban Development Council<ref>{{cite web |title=Samoohya Sevana Puraskaram |url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/31230347_1510388972422227_1512303240991997952_n.jpg?_nc_cat=102&_nc_ohc=GPuRCvA8CyEAX-LBiuG&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=1312ae277de078e98facb02c0a0f6fa1&oe=5EB0EE47 |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=2018}}</ref>\n* 2018: Gem of Kerala (Keralaratnam) from Global Confederation of Pravasee Malayalees<ref>{{cite web|title=Keralarathnam Puraskaram for Dr. Rajith Kumar|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/37098494_1617139401747183_4986265561013944320_n.jpg?_nc_cat=101&_nc_ohc=myJshFYFuqYAX_pc2VC&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=a4a011cd888337fdaac55dfc00240dd4&oe=5EA2C2C5|accessdate=8 January 2020|date=2019}}</ref>\n* 2018: Gurushreshta Puraskaram from Vanitha Congress (M)<ref>{{cite web|title=Gurushreshta Puraskaram|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/s960x960/33895718_1552916591502798_6648791957562720256_o.jpg?_nc_cat=101&_nc_ohc=kC4gY6REo3oAX_xBakA&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&_nc_tp=1&oh=a265ed2c11a36a909ea94ea2175e01fd&oe=5E9E5B5A|accessdate=8 January 2020|date=2019}}</ref>\n* 2019: Shri. Vedavyasa Puraskaram from Bharatiya Dalit Sahitya Akademi<ref>{{cite web|title=Shri Vedavyasa Puraskaram|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/70432109_2278437895617327_7433235599231811584_n.jpg?_nc_cat=110&_nc_ohc=cnj38fBFi_kAX8DmwPF&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=7476697f464464910e1eb6ed375af1f4&oe=5EA9CE25|accessdate=8 January 2020|date=2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|UCk4VIY579X-3Y6RHPBuhr-Q|Dr.Rajith Kumar}}\n* {{Facebook|rajith.kumar.14473}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kumar, Rajith}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian philosophers]]\n[[Category:People from Thiruvananthapuram district]]\n[[Category:Social critics]]\n[[Category:Malayali people]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language writers]]\n[[Category:Indian activists]]\n[[Category:Indian academics]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Rajith Kumar\n| image         = Rajith Kumar.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Rajith in 2016\n| birth_name    = Rajith Kumar R.\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = [[Attingal]], [[Thiruvananthapuram district|Trivandrum<!--Thiruvananthapuram was known as Trivandrum until 1991-->]], [[Kerala]], India\n| other_names   = Dr. Rajith Kumar, DRK\n| occupation    = {{hlist|Public speaker|Lecturer|Educational counselor|Writer|Philanthropist}}\n| years_active  = 1996 \u2013 present (Lecturing)\n| spouse        = \n}}\n'''Rajith Kumar R.'''  is an Indian [[public speaker]], lecturer, [[School counselor|educational counselor]], writer, and [[philanthropist]] from [[Kerala]]. He works as a lecturer in the Botany department of [[Sree Sankara College]], [[Kalady]].<!--Per WP:TAGBOMBING, adding unnecessary tags counts as vandalism. Lead is a summary of body and does not require citation. Content is already cited in the body.--> He has authored more than ten books, related to self-improvement and religious texts. Some of his statements made in public speeches has been the subject of controversy. Rajith is an active humanitarian worker, he founded the \"Dr. Rajith Charitable Services\" and is a life-member of [[Indian Red Cross Society]].\n\nRajith holds a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (Ph.D.) in [[microbiology]] and [[Master of Philosophy]] (M. Phil) in [[cytogenetics]].<!--Per WP:TAGBOMBING, adding unnecessary tags counts as vandalism. Lead is a summary of body and does not require citation. Content is already cited in the body.--> He has received several awards and honours, including the Samoohya Saksharatha Prathibha award from Kerala State Literacy Mission Authority, [[Government of Kerala]]. In 2020, Rajith contested in the [[Bigg Boss (Malayalam season 2)|second season]] of Malayalam [[reality TV]] show ''[[Bigg Boss (Malayalam TV series)|Bigg Boss]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nRajith Kumar hails from Kizhuvilam, [[Attingal]] in [[Thiruvananthapuram district]] of [[Kerala]], India. His father died before he was born, his mother was a last grade government employee in the health department. He had his schooling from Government Model Boys Higher Secondary School, Attingal. Rajith was adjudged Best Student while studying at [[Mar Ivanios College]] in Thiruvananthapuram, from where he graduated with a bachelor's degree ([[Bachelor of Science|B.Sc]]) in [[botany]] and had his master's degree ([[Master of Science|M.Sc]]) from [[N. S. S. College, Pandalam]] with first rank.<ref name=\"TH-article\">{{cite news|last=Pradeep|first=K.|title=Teaching from the heart|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/Teaching-from-the-heart/article16369919.ece|accessdate=1 February 2020|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=5 November 2009}}</ref> He then took a [[Master of Philosophy]] (M. Phil) in [[cytogenetics]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (Ph.D) in [[microbiology]] (passed with [[gold medal]]<ref name=\"TNIE-article\"/>). He also went on to take a [[Bachelor of Education]] (B.Ed) degree in [[natural science]], a bachelor's degree in [[library and information science]] (BLIS), a master's degree (M.S) in [[psychotherapy]], and a diploma in [[Vedanta]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.asianetnews.com/biggboss/bigg-boss-malayalam-season-two-contestant-rajith-kumar-q3n3k1|title=\u0d05\u0d24\u0d46 \u0d07\u0d24\u0d4d \u0d30\u0d1c\u0d3f\u0d24\u0d4d \u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d \u0d24\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d46! \u0d2c\u0d3f\u0d17\u0d4d \u0d2c\u0d4b\u0d38\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d \u0d0e\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d41\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d24\u0d4d \u0d35\u0d28\u0d4d\u200d \u0d2e\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d35\u0d31\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d4d\u200d|work=[[Asianet News]]|language=ml|author=Web desk|date=5 January 2020|accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dr.Rajith Kumar in Janakeiya Kodathi {{!}} Dr.\u0d30\u0d1c\u0d3f\u0d24\u0d4d \u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d7c \u0d1c\u0d28\u0d15\u0d40\u0d2f \u0d15\u0d4b\u0d1f\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d4d\u200d {{!}} Ep# 13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HWpyLcjk6Tw|publisher=24 News|accessdate=21 January 2020|language=ml|date=3 March 2019}}</ref> He has also passed the [[UGC NET]] examination.<ref name=\"TNIE-article\"/>\n\n==Work==\nIn 1996, he joined as a lecturer in Botany department at [[Sree Sankara College]], [[Kalady]] and continued there until 2003. Since his mother refused to leave his hometown [[Attingal]] to stay with him, he took a transfer to Government Model Boys Higher Secondary School, Attingal (where he studied) to a lower position as a teacher even after receiving a doctorate. But later he was transferred back to Sree Sankara College and visited mother at weekends. In 2009, the [[Thiruvananthapuram district]] panchayat nominated and selected him as a member of its Working Group. In September 2009, the [[Chirayinkeezhu]] panchayat and Kerala State Literacy Mission Authority honoured him with Samoohya Saksharatha Prathibha award.<ref name=\"TH-article\"/> He convened \"Keralagramam\", an [[Indian Science Congress Association]] programme held in Thiruvananthapuram in 2010.<ref name=\"TNIE-article\"/>\n\nRajith is an active humanitarian worker, he founded the Dr. Rajith Charitable Services and is a life-member of [[Indian Red Cross Society]]. From 2000s, he has been offering free coaching classes, counselling sessions, uniforms, textbooks, medicine, food among other things to economically backward students, funded from his own salary. By 2009, number of such students he gave assistance surpassed 25,000. Rajith has taken part in training programmes conducted by [[National Council of Educational Research and Training|NCERT]] and [[State Council of Educational Research and Training, Kerala|SCERT]] in adolescent education.<ref name=\"TNIE-article\">{{cite news|last=Prakash|first=Asha|title=The power of one|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/thiruvananthapuram/2009/dec/08/the-power-of-one-111052.html|accessdate=1 February 2020|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=8 December 2009}}</ref> He is also known for his public awareness speeches. He has authored more than ten books in [[Malayalam]], related to religion and personal motivation.\n\nHe appeared in the children's [[feature film]] ''Manalchithrangal'' (2015). In 2018, he appeared in the short film ''Daivathinte Naadu'', and in a music video, ''Amma'', in the following year. In 2020, he entered the Bigg Boss house as a contestant in the [[reality television]] show [[Bigg Boss (Malayalam season 2)|''Bigg Boss'' (Malayalam season 2)]] on [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/bigg-boss-malayalam-2-contestant-dr-rajith-kumar-everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-controversial-public-speaker/articleshow/73111049.cms|title=Bigg Boss Malayalam 2 contestant Dr Rajith Kumar: Everything you need to know about the controversial public speaker|work=The Times of India|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> When he was ousted from the show, his supporters organized a public gathering to welcome him at [[Cochin International Airport]]. The gathering was organized despite the government's cautionary measures against the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kerala|coronavirus pandemic]]. Rajith and 79 other people involved in the gathering were booked by the police for flouting government advisory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 79 Booked for Organising Mass Reception for Bigg Boss Malayalam 2 Contestant Rajith Kumar |url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/coronavirus-79-booked-for-organising-mass-reception-for-bigg-boss-malayalam-2-contestant-rajith-kumar-2538089.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=News18 |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Rajith Kumar, 11 others taken into custody by Kerala police for flouting COVID-19 advisory |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/2020/mar/17/rajith-kumar-taken-into-custody-by-kerala-police-for-flouting-covid-19-advisory-2117809.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The New Indian Express}}</ref> He was released on bail after questioning.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bigg Boss Malayalam 2's Rajith Kumar, arrested over unlawful assembly, granted bail|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/bigg-boss-malayalam-2s-rajith-kumar-arrested-over-unlawful-assembly-granted-bail/articleshow/74684593.cms|accessdate=19 March 2020|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==In the media==\nIn 2013, while speaking at [[Government College for Women, Thiruvananthapuram]] at the \"moral education\" campaign organised by the [[Department of General and Higher Education (Kerala)|Department of General and Higher Education]], he criticised women's current dressing style. It received media attention after a student protested by booing and boycotting the speech. [[Shobhana George]] complained against his statement in the [[Kerala State Human Rights Commission]] which asked the Collegiate Education Department to enquire into the matter. [[Deputy Director]] Girija Devi who conducted the enquiry reported that Kumar's speech was \"a piece of art and the opposition by a graduate student to the speech was an immature response\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Now, Rajith Kumar's misogyny becomes 'art'|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/thiruvananthapuram/Now-Rajith-Kumars-misogyny-becomes-art/articleshow/20596003.cms|accessdate=2 October 2019|date=15 June 2013|work=[[The Times of India]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, in a counselling session held in [[Kasaragod]] he reportedly stated that women who wear [[jeans]] can give birth to [[transgender]] children and the children born to rebel men and women is found to be [[Autism|autistic]], claiming to have scientific backing. He received rebuke, with media and public calling it ill-informed, unscientific, and offensive. Kumar defended it saying that there are efforts to put him in bad light and only a certain portion from his 4-hour long speech was taken and is used to create misunderstanding among people. He reiterated and defended his statements again in the show ''Njangalkum Parayanund'' in [[Mathrubhumi News]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Varier |first1=Megha |title='Wearing jeans leads to birth of trans kids': Kerala Prof slammed for offensive remarks |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/wearing-jeans-leads-birth-trans-kids-kerala-prof-slammed-offensive-remark-78960 |accessdate=2 October 2019|work=[[The News Minute]]|date=3 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Women who dress like men, wear jeans give birth to transgenders: Kerala professor|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/040418/women-who-dress-like-men-give-birth-to-transkids-kerala-professor.html|accessdate=2 October 2019|date=4 April 2018|work=[[Deccan Chronicle]]}}</ref> Following that, health minister [[K. K. Shailaja]] released a press note barring Kumar from speaking in government programmes, citing that he spreads superstition and social discord.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/state-to-initiate-action-against-counsellor/article23415500.ece|title=State to initiate action against counsellor|date=2 April 2018|work=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=3 April 2018|author=Special correspondent|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Although his statements has received criticism, he has also found support from a section of public.<ref>{{cite web|last=Raja|first=Vidya|title='Women in Jeans' Give Birth to Trans Kids. Really? and You Claim to Be a Botany Lecturer|url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/136946/rajith-kumar-ridiculous-statements-women-jeans-kerala/|accessdate=2 October 2019|date=6 April 2018|publisher=[[The Better India]]}}</ref> Following the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kerala]], he said that he had a 'pure heart' and therefore he cannot be infected with coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rajith Kumar fans' airport gathering exposes Kerala's coronavirus preventive system |url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/news/kerala/2020/03/16/bigg-boss-rajith-kumar-fans-gathering-intelligence-failure-corona-scare.html |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=OnManorama |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Thiricharivu: The Power of Discrimination''<ref>{{cite web|title=Thiricharivu: The Power of Discrimination|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/s960x960/1669853_464073380387130_973326160_o.jpg?_nc_cat=105&_nc_oc=AQmWiW0WLG9wdrRa7PQxXvZubjuV1gXmzxVriBrdmw3frAh6MTOAKOVfOwqN31n1R_sC8GhkPWj-vCfImZb1sZD7&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=0f2fddda4f18f046abd7860d76956a4a&oe=5ECFC045|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Enne Vismayipicha Quran Sookthangal''<ref>{{cite web|title=Enne Vismayipicha Quran Sookthangal|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/s960x960/20989207_1277625682365225_6944141026383949430_o.jpg?_nc_cat=106&_nc_oc=AQmIeJtHzBKCEcLRob4-4Fk79BG_PCoZ2ceRLkx7NWD7yxYcOyduJYPEI4pZTPnStLHzm2QnR3XxRwmw1x6Znicx&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=10978df51bb0bdcbae5fd3dba58550b7&oe=5EC2A2BF|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Srimad Bhagavad Gita Sandhesham''\n* ''Ennil Karunaniracha Bible''<ref>{{cite web|title=Ennil Karunaniracha Bible|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/s960x960/25627047_1424355261025599_9019249648867682904_o.jpg?_nc_cat=107&_nc_ohc=zkKIZjh0MP8AX8GsB10&_nc_ht=scontent.fcok1-1.fna&oh=c6c1cfab63ecc3ec25a61da13b868577&oe=5EBF573E|publisher=Dr. Rajith Kumar|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Unaru Unaru''<ref>{{cite web|title=Unaru Unaru|url=https://scontent.fcok1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/s960x960/12513483_800966413364490_5972552697250588791_o.jpg?_nc_cat=109&_nc_oc=AQk1VQUH