esh\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[D 4 Dance|D3 \u2013 D4 Dance]]''\n| Guest\n| [[Mazhavil Manorama]]\n| Along with Abhirami Suresh\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Smart Show''\n| Participant\n| [[Flowers (TV channel)|Flowers]]\n| Along with Abhirami Suresh <br>Opposite Stephen Devassy & Merin Gregory\n|-\n|\n| ''Mylanchi Little Champions''\n| Guest Singer\n| [[Asianet]]\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Chat with Amrutha Suresh''\n| Guest\n| [[Kaumudy TV]]\n| Talk show\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Varthakkappuram''\n| Guest\n| [[Asianet News]]\n| Talk show\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Music Shots''\n| Singer\n| [[Manorama Online]]\n| \n|-\n|2017 || ''Miss & Mrs Kerala Beauty Pageant 2017'' || Performer || [[Kairali TV]] ||Alongside Amruthamgamaya band \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Moodtapes''\n| Singer\n| [[Kappa TV]]\n| \n|-\n|2017 \n| ''Amruthamgamaya'' \n| Guest \n| [[News18 Kerala]] \n| Along with Abhirami Suresh\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''The Happiness Project''\n| Guest\n| [[Kappa TV]]\n| Talk show\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Paadaam Namukku Padaam''\n| Guest\n| [[Mazhavil Manorama]]\n| Along with Abhirami Suresh\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Mazhavil Music Awards''\n| Herself\n| [[Mazhavil Manorama]]\n| Award ceremony; nominated for \"Minni Minni\" in ''[[June (film)|June]]''\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Josh Talks''\n| Herself\n| [[Josh Talks]]\n| Talk show\n|-\n| 2020\n| [[Bigg Boss (Malayalam season 2)|''Bigg Boss'' (Malayalam season 2)]]\n| Herself\n| [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]]\n| [[Reality TV]] competition; paired with Abhirami Suresh \n|}\n\n==Online appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2017 \n \t\t\n| ''How Well Do You Know'' \n \t\t\n| Guest \n \t\t\n| FWD TV Online \n \t\n| Chat show\n \t\n|-\n| 2017 \n \t\t\n| '' IndiaGlitz Malayalam Movies Interview\t'' \n \t\t\n| Guest \n \t\t\n| IndiaGlitz Online \n \t\n| Chat show\n \t\n|-\n| 2017 \n \t\t\n| '' Sensations Entertainment\t'' \n \t\t\n| Guest \n \t\t\n| Online\n \t\n| Talk show\n|-\n| 2019\n \t\t\n| ''Movie Man''\n \t\t\n| Herself\n \t\t\n| Online\n \t\t\n| Talk show\n \t\t\n|-\n \t\t\n| 2019\n \t\t\n| ''Red FM Red Carpet''\n \t\t\n| Herself\n \t\t\n| Red FM Malayalam Online\n \t\t\n| Talk show\n \t\t\n|-\n \t\t\n| 2019\n \t\t\n| ''Candid Chat with Mammootty''\n \t\t\n| Interviewer\n \t\t\n| Sillymonks Online\n \t\t\n| Talk show\n \t\t\n|-\n \t\t\n| 2019\n \t\t\n| ''Oppo Kerala 4th Anniversary  ''\n \t\t\n| Performer\n \t\t\n| Youtube\n \t\t\n| Stage show\n \t\t\n|-\n| 2019\n \t\t\n| ''Vanita Utsav ''\n \t\t\n| Performer\n \t\t\n| Youtube\n \t\t\n| Stage show\n \t\t\n|-\t\t\n| 2020\n \t\t\n| ''Iam the Answer''\n \t\t\n| Herself\n \t\t\n| Vanitha Online\n \t\t\n| Talk show\n \t\n|-\n \t\t\n| 2020\n \t\t\n| ''Choych Choych Powam''\n \t\t\n| Herself\n \t\t\n| Ginger Media Broadcasting Online\n \t\t\n| Talk show\n \t\t\n|-\n \t\t\n| 2020\n \t\t\n| ''Be It''\n \t\t\n| Herself\n \t\t\n| Online\n \t\n| Talk show\n \t\t\n|-\n\t\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n* Creative Film Awards 2019 - for Best Singer Female - June <ref>https://pycker.com/news/creative-film-awards-2019-kayamkulam-kochunni-and-june-win-big/164311802789180</ref>\n* Ramu Kairat Sangeetha Award for Best Solo 2019 - June \n* Master Vision International Excellence Award (Singer) 2017\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://amrutamgamay.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|nm10374814}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suresh, Amrutha}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian women singers]]\n[[Category:Indian female film singers]]\n[[Category:Indian female pop singers]]\n[[Category:Indian female folk singers]]\n[[Category:Indian women ghazal singers]]\n[[Category:Bhajan singers]]\n[[Category:Hindustani singers]]\n[[Category:Female Carnatic singers]]\n[[Category:Malayalam playback singers]]\n[[Category:Indian female composers]]\n[[Category:Indian female songwriters]]\n[[Category:Singers from Kochi]]\n[[Category:Indian women radio presenters]]\n[[Category:Singing talent show contestants]]\n[[Category:Bigg Boss contestants]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toAsianet(link changed toAsianet (TV channel)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amrutha_Suresh"}
{"title_page": "Grahame Farr", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Grahame Farr\n| honorific_suffix = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1912|10|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Clifton, Bristol]]\n| death_date       = {{death date and age |1983|11|22|1912|10|27|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = Maritime historian\n| language         = English\n| residence        = [[Portishead, Somerset]]\n| nationality      = British\n| education        = [[Clifton College]]\n| alma_mater       = \n| home_town        = \n| period           = 1935-1983\n| subject          = History of ships, shipping and lifeboats\n| notableworks     = ''Records of Bristol Ships, 1800-1838'' (Bristol, 1950)<br />''Somerset Harbours, including the Port of Bristol'' (London, 1954)<br />''West Country passenger steamers'' (Second, revised, edition, Prescot, 1967).\n| spouse           = Elsie Farr\n| awards           = \n}}\n'''Grahame Edgar Farr''' (27 October 1912 \u2013 22 November 1983) was a [[Maritime history|maritime historian]], specialising in the history of ships and shipping in the south-west of England from the eighteenth century onwards.  He also wrote about the history of the [[Lifeboat (rescue)|lifeboat]].\n\nFarr was born, educated, lived and worked in [[Bristol]]; his interest in ships and shipping came from his father, and his upbringing in Bristol. Farr worked for a printing firm; his research and writing therefore had to be conducted in his spare time.  Farr wrote many books on maritime history; the most notable being ''Records of Bristol Ships, 1800-1838''; ''Somerset Harbours, including the Port of Bristol''; and ''West Country passenger steamers''.  He archives are held by the [[National Maritime Museum]] and the Friends of [[Purton Hulks|Purton]].\n\n==Early life==\nFarr was born in [[Clifton, Bristol]] on 27 October 1912.<ref>{{cite news |title=Briths |work=Western Daily Press |date=29 October 1912 |page=10}}</ref>  His father was Edgar James Farr, who worked for the [[Bristol General Steam Navigation Company|Bristol Steam Navigation Company]] for 50 years, starting as an office boy and finishing as an accountant.<ref>{{cite news |title=50 Years with Shipping Firm |work=Western Daily Press |date=1 July 1950 |page=10}}</ref>  The ''[[Western Daily Press]]'' described Edgar Farr as \u2018A well-known figure in Bristol shipping circles\u2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Death of Mr E. J. Farr |work=Western Daily Press |date=8 November 1950 |page=4}}</ref>  Farr's interest in ships and shipping came from his father, and his upbringing in Bristol.<ref name=\"MM70(1)\">{{cite journal |last1=BROCK |first1=P. W. |last2=MCGOWAN |first2=ALAN |last3=BROMLEY |first3=J. S. |last4=GODDARD |first4=E. O. C. |last5=CRAIG |first5=ROBIN |title=OBITUARIES |journal=The Mariner's Mirror |date=January 1984 |volume=70 |issue=1 |pages=3\u20136 |doi=10.1080/00253359.1984.10655947}}</ref>\n\nFarr was educated at [[Clifton College]] (presumably as a day-boy, as his family lived in Clifton).<ref>{{cite news |title=Shipping Taverns of Bristol |work=Western Daily Press |date=5 January 1935 |page=7}}</ref><ref name=\"MM70(1)\" />\n\n==Career==\nOn leaving Clifton College, Farr worked for a printing firm in Bristol, where he stayed for the whole of his professional life, apart from his war service. Farr's research and writing had to be conducted in his spare time.<ref name=\"MM70(1)\" />\n\nDuring the [[World War II|Second World War]], Farr served with the [[Royal Army Service Corps]] (RASC), being made [[Second lieutenant|Second Lieutenant]] on 23 November 1940 ([[Service number#United Kingdom|service number]] 158967).<ref>{{cite news |title=Royal Army Service Corps. |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/35008/supplement/6927 |accessdate=5 November 2019 |work=The London Gazette |issue=Supplement: 35008 |date=3 December 1940 |page=6927}}</ref>  By 1944 he was a War Substantive Lieutenant.<ref>{{cite news |title=Royal Army Service Corps. |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/36700/supplement/4256 |accessdate=5 November 2019 |work=The London Gazette |issue=Supplement: 36700 |date=12 September 1944 |page=4256}}</ref> His war service took him to Kenya, Madagascar and Ceylon.<ref name=\"MM70(1)\" />\n\nFarr was an early member of the Bristol Shiplovers Society (founded in 1931);<ref>{{cite news |title=Local Notes and Topics : Ship Lovers |work=Western Daily Press |date=1 December 1931 |page=7}}</ref> he became its Honorary Secretary before the war.<ref>{{cite news |title=Literary Society : Interesting Season in Prospect at St. Luke's |work=Bath Chronicle and Weekly Gazette |date=8 October 1938 |page=8}}</ref>  An objective of the society was to \u2018collect data, past and present, of ships and sailors, chiefly relating to the Port of Bristol. These facts are entered into the log-books of the society and due course recorded in the archives of Bristol\u2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=For Lovers of Ships |work=Western Daily Press |date=30 September 1949 |page=6}}</ref> During the war, his father, Edgar Farr, acted as secretary to Bristol Shiplovers Society on his son's behalf.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shiplovers |work=Western Daily Press |date=22 February 1940 |page=5}}</ref>\n\nFarr also became a member of the [[Society for Nautical Research]], continuing as a member for nearly 50 years.  His earliest article for the Society's journal, ''[[The Mariner's Mirror]]'', was about Brunel's [[SS Great Western|Great Western]], built in Bristol.  It was published in 1938.<ref name=\"MM70(1)\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Farr |first1=Grahame E. |title=THE GREAT WESTERN |journal=The Mariner's Mirror |date=January 1938 |volume=24 |issue=2 |pages=131\u2013152 |doi=10.1080/00253359.1938.10657279}}</ref>\n\nFarr's earliest book was ''The Somersetshire Life-Boats'' (Bristol, 1935).\n\nFollowing the war, Farr wrote many books on [[maritime history]], specialising in the history of ships and shipping in the [[West Country]] from the eighteenth century onwards.  He wrote several monographs for the [[National Maritime Museum]]. Farr also contributed articles to journals, including ''The Mariner's Mirror''. He was the first maritime historian to make intensive use of the Statutory Registers of Merchant Ships.<ref name=\"MM70(1)\" />\n\nFarr was the archivist of the Lifeboat Enthusiasts' Society. The Society was formed in 1964, with the active co-operation of the [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution]], 'to facilitate communication between persons interested in the technical and historical aspects of life-boat work'.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=FARR |first1=GRAHAME |last2=GLASGOW |first2=TOM |last3=PULLEN |first3=H. F. |last4=DE COURCY |first4=J. |last5=DE COURCY |first5=J. |last6=LATCHAM |first6=P. R. |title=QUERIES |journal=The Mariner's Mirror |date=January 1968 |volume=54 |issue=3 |pages=304\u2013305 |doi=10.1080/00253359.1968.10659451}}</ref> Farr was also the honorary editor of the International Lifeboat Journal between 1974 and 1983.<ref name=\"Lifeboat_48_486\">{{cite news |title=Three Lifeboat People |url=https://rnliarchive.blob.core.windows.net/media/1474/0486.pdf#page=4 |accessdate=5 November 2019 |work=The Lifeboat : Journal of the Royal National Lifeboat Institution |issue=Volume: 48 Issue: 486 |date=Autumn 1983}}</ref><ref name=\"MM70(1)\" />\n\nFarr died on 22 November 1983,<ref name=\"Lifeboat_48_486\" /> after a long struggle against deteriorating health and eyesight. His obituary in ''The Mariner\u2019s Mirror'' described him as \u2018a remarkable man, assiduous and painstaking in his research, and yet ever-ready to share his knowledge with others\u2019.<ref name=\"MM70(1)\" />\n\n==Works by Grahame Farr==\nWorks by Farr are variously catalogued under the names Grahame Edgar Farr, Grahame E. Farr, Grahame Farr, and G. E. Farr.  The following lists are largely derived from the catalogue of the [[British Library]].\n\n===''Wreck and rescue'' series, published by D. Bradford Barton, Truro===\n*''Wreck and rescue round the Cornish coast. 1. The Story of the north coast Lifeboats.'' (With Cyril Noall.) Truro, 1964.\n*''Wreck and rescue round the Cornish coast. 2. The Story of the Land's End lifeboats.'' (With Cyril Noall.) Truro, 1965.\n*''Wreck and rescue round the Cornish coast. 3. The Story of the south coast lifeboats.'' (With Cyril Noall.) Truro, 1965.\n*''Wreck and rescue in the Bristol Channel. 1. The Story of the English Lifeboats.'' Truro, 1966.\n*''Wreck and rescue in the Bristol Channel. 2. The story of the Welsh lifeboats.'' Truro, 1967.\n*''Wreck and rescue on the coast of Devon. The Story of the South Devon Lifeboats.'' Truro, 1968.\n*''Wreck and rescue on the Dorset coast. The story of the Dorset lifeboats.'' Truro, 1971.\n\n===Papers on life-boat history (self-published)===\n*No. 1: ''William Plenty's life boats, 1817-29 : and James and Edward Pellew Plenty's life boat model, 1851.'' Portishead, 1975.\n*No. 2: ''George Palmer's life-boats, 1828-47 : with allied types and variants.'' Portishead, 1975.\n*No. 3: ''Life-boats of the Shipwrecked Fishermen and Mariners' Royal Benevolent Society, 1851-4.'' Portishead, 1976.\n*No. 4: ''The tubular life-boats, 1850-1939.'' Portishead, 1977.\n*No. 5: ''The steam life-boats : with notes on earlier projects, and overseas steam life-boats.'' Portishead, 1981.\n*No. 6: ''The Lincolnshire Coast Shipwreck Association 1827-1864.'' Portishead, 1981.\n\n===Aids to life-boat history (self-published)===\n*No. 1: ''Hand-list of R.N.L.I. official numbers : and operational numbers.'' Portishead, 1978.\n*No. 2: ''British life-boat stations : a historical and geographical list.'' Portishead, 1979.\n\n===Maritime monographs and reports, published by the National Maritime Museum===\n*No. 20: ''The ship registers of the Port of Hayle, 1864-1882.'' Greenwich, 1975.\n*No. 22: ''Shipbuilding in North Devon : containing a list of the vessels known to have been built on the North Devon coast and rivers, with an introduction, notes on the builders, appendices, tables and a map.'' Greenwich, 1976.\n\n===Other Books===\n*''The Somersetshire Life-Boats. A brief history of rescue work on the Somersetshire coast.'' Bristol, 1935.\n*''[https://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/History/bristolrecordsociety/publications/brs15.pdf Records of Bristol Ships, 1800-1838. Vessels over 150 tons.]'' Bristol, 1950.\n*''Somerset Harbours, including the Port of Bristol.'' London, 1954.\n*''Chepstow Ships.'' Chepstow, 1954.\n*''West Country Passenger Steamers.'' London, 1956.\n*''The Bristol Shiplovers' Society, 1931-1956.'' Bristol, 1957.\n*''The Steamship Great Western: the first Atlantic liner.'' Bristol, 1963.\n*''The Steamship Great Britain.'' Bristol, 1965.\n*''West Country passenger steamers.'' Second edition. Prescot, 1967.\n*''Cornish shipwrecks.'' (With Cyril Noall.) Truro, 1969.\n*''Ships and Harbours of Exmoor (Microstudy).'' Dulverton, 1970.\n*''Bristol shipbuilding in the nineteenth century.'' Bristol, 1971.\n*''Ships and Harbours of Exmoor (Microstudy).'' Second edition. Dulverton, 1974.\n*''Penlee Lifeboat: History of the Penlee and Penzance Branch of the R.N.L.I.'' (With John Corin.) Penzance, 1983.\n\n==Archives==\n[[National Maritime Museum]] holds Farr's card index system for ships entering the Bristol Channel (between Milford, Gloucester and the Scilly Isles). Information in the cards \u2018include the name of the vessel (arranged in the index alphabetically); port of registry and date which includes ports UK wide; an abbreviation description of the vessel (no guide to abbreviations available); dimensions; tonnage; builders; engines; the first owners and if any changes were made to the vessel\u2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Uncatalogued: Farr, Grahame Edgar, 1912-1983, Shipping Historian: Card Index for vessels entering the Bristol Channel |url=https://collections.rmg.co.uk/archive/objects/463657.html |website=The Collection |publisher=Royal Museums Greenwich |accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Friends of [[Purton Hulks|Purton]] acquired Farr's photographic collection in 2007. Started in the 1930s, the collection consists of several thousand black and white images of local schooners, trows, lighters, coasters, paddle steamers and related subjects.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barnett |first1=Paul |title=Graham Farr photographic collection |url=http://www.cotswoldcanalsheritage.org.uk/page_id__199.aspx?path=0p2p29p |website=Cotswold Canals Heritage |publisher=Cotswold Canals Heritage |accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Webery : The Grahame Farr Photographic Collection |journal=South West Soundings : The Newsletter of the South West Maritime History Society |date=March 2010 |issue= 78 |page=27 |url=https://www.swmaritime.org.uk/_webedit/uploaded-files/All%20Files/SWS78.pdf |accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Exmoor]] Society's archives include extensive material relating to the commissioning and publication of Farr's microstudy on the \u2018\u2019Ships and Harbours of Exmoor\u2019\u2019 (Dulverton, 1970, second edition 1974).<ref>{{cite web |title=Farr's Ships and Harbours : Material relating to Farr\u2019s microstudy on the Ships and Harbours of Exmoor |url=https://www.exmoorsociety.com/content/catalogue_item/victor-bonham-carter-papers/exmoor-press-papers/farrs-ships-and-harbours |website=The Exmoor Society |publisher=The Exmoor Society |accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Farr, Grahame}}\n[[Category:British maritime historians|Farr, Grahame]]\n[[Category:1912 births|Farr, Grahame]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths|Farr, Grahame]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Grahame Farr\n| honorific_suffix = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1912|10|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Clifton, Bristol]]\n| death_date       = {{death date and age |1983|11|22|1912|10|27|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = Maritime historian\n| language         = English\n| residence        = [[Portishead, Somerset]]\n| nationality      = British\n| education        = [[Clifton College]]\n| alma_mater       = \n| home_town        = \n| period           = 1935-1983\n| subject          = History of ships, shipping and lifeboats\n| notableworks     = ''Records of Bristol Ships, 1800-1838'' (Bristol, 1950)<br />''Somerset Harbours, including the Port of Bristol'' (London, 1954)<br />''West Country passenger steamers'' (Second, revised, edition, Prescot, 1967).\n| spouse           = Elsie Farr\n| awards           = \n}}\n'''Grahame Edgar Farr''' (27 October 1912 \u2013 22 November 1983) was a [[Maritime history|maritime historian]], specialising in the history of ships and shipping in the south-west of England from the eighteenth century onwards.  He also wrote about the history of the [[Lifeboat (rescue)|lifeboat]].\n\nFarr was born, educated, lived and worked in [[Bristol]]; his interest in ships and shipping came from his father, and his upbringing in Bristol. Farr worked for a printing firm; his research and writing therefore had to be conducted in his spare time.  Farr wrote many books on maritime history; the most notable being ''Records of Bristol Ships, 1800-1838''; ''Somerset Harbours, including the Port of Bristol''; and ''West Country passenger steamers''.  He archives are held by the [[National Maritime Museum]] and the Friends of [[Purton Hulks|Purton]].\n\n==Early life==\nFarr was born in [[Clifton, Bristol]] on 27 October 1912.<ref>{{cite news |title=Briths |work=Western Daily Press |date=29 October 1912 |page=10}}</ref>  His father was Edgar James Farr, who worked for the [[Bristol General Steam Navigation Company|Bristol Steam Navigation Company]] for 50 years, starting as an office boy and finishing as an accountant.<ref>{{cite news |title=50 Years with Shipping Firm |work=Western Daily Press |date=1 July 1950 |page=10}}</ref>  The ''[[Western Daily Press]]'' described Edgar Farr as \u2018A well-known figure in Bristol shipping circles\u2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Death of Mr E. J. Farr |work=Western Daily Press |date=8 November 1950 |page=4}}</ref>  Farr's interest in ships and shipping came from his father, and his upbringing in Bristol.<ref name=\"MM70(1)\">{{cite journal |last1=BROCK |first1=P. W. |last2=MCGOWAN |first2=ALAN |last3=BROMLEY |first3=J. S. |last4=GODDARD |first4=E. O. C. |last5=CRAIG |first5=ROBIN |title=OBITUARIES |journal=The Mariner's Mirror |date=January 1984 |volume=70 |issue=1 |pages=3\u20136 |doi=10.1080/00253359.1984.10655947}}</ref>\n\nFarr was educated at [[Clifton College]] (presumably as a day-boy, as his family lived in Clifton).<ref>{{cite news |title=Shipping Taverns of Bristol |work=Western Daily Press |date=5 January 1935 |page=7}}</ref><ref name=\"MM70(1)\" />\n\n==Career==\nOn leaving Clifton College, Farr worked for a printing firm in Bristol, where he stayed for the whole of his professional life, apart from his war service. Farr's research and writing had to be conducted in his spare time.<ref name=\"MM70(1)\" />\n\nDuring the [[World War II|Second World War]], Farr served with the [[Royal Army Service Corps]] (RASC), being made [[Second lieutenant|Second Lieutenant]] on 23 November 1940 ([[Service number#United Kingdom|service number]] 158967).<ref>{{cite news |title=Royal Army Service Corps. |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/35008/supplement/6927 |accessdate=5 November 2019 |work=The London Gazette |issue=Supplement: 35008 |date=3 December 1940 |page=6927}}</ref>  By 1944 he was a War Substantive Lieutenant.<ref>{{cite news |title=Royal Army Service Corps. |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/36700/supplement/4256 |accessdate=5 November 2019 |work=The London Gazette |issue=Supplement: 36700 |date=12 September 1944 |page=4256}}</ref> His war service took him to Kenya, Madagascar and Ceylon.<ref name=\"MM70(1)\" />\n\nFarr was an early member of the Bristol Shiplovers Society (founded in 1931);<ref>{{cite news |title=Local Notes and Topics : Ship Lovers |work=Western Daily Press |date=1 December 1931 |page=7}}</ref> he became its Honorary Secretary before the war.<ref>{{cite news |title=Literary Society : Interesting Season in Prospect at St. Luke's |work=Bath Chronicle and Weekly Gazette |date=8 October 1938 |page=8}}</ref>  An objective of the society was to \u2018collect data, past and present, of ships and sailors, chiefly relating to the Port of Bristol. These facts are entered into the log-books of the society and due course recorded in the archives of Bristol\u2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=For Lovers of Ships |work=Western Daily Press |date=30 September 1949 |page=6}}</ref> During the war, his father, Edgar Farr, acted as secretary to Bristol Shiplovers Society on his son's behalf.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shiplovers |work=Western Daily Press |date=22 February 1940 |page=5}}</ref>\n\nFarr also became a member of the [[Society for Nautical Research]], continuing as a member for nearly 50 years.  His earliest article for the Society's journal, ''[[The Mariner's Mirror]]'', was about Brunel's [[SS Great Western|Great Western]], built in Bristol.  It was published in 1938.<ref name=\"MM70(1)\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Farr |first1=Grahame E. |title=THE GREAT WESTERN |journal=The Mariner's Mirror |date=January 1938 |volume=24 |issue=2 |pages=131\u2013152 |doi=10.1080/00253359.1938.10657279}}</ref>\n\nFarr's earliest book was ''The Somersetshire Life-Boats'' (Bristol, 1935).\n\nFollowing the war, Farr wrote many books on [[maritime history]], specialising in the history of ships and shipping in the [[West Country]] from the eighteenth century onwards.  He wrote several monographs for the [[National Maritime Museum]]. Farr also contributed articles to journals, including ''The Mariner's Mirror''. He was the first maritime historian to make intensive use of the Statutory Registers of Merchant Ships.<ref name=\"MM70(1)\" />\n\nFarr was the archivist of the Lifeboat Enthusiasts' Society. The Society was formed in 1964, with the active co-operation of the [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution]], 'to facilitate communication between persons interested in the technical and historical aspects of life-boat work'.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=FARR |first1=GRAHAME |last2=GLASGOW |first2=TOM |last3=PULLEN |first3=H. F. |last4=DE COURCY |first4=J. |last5=DE COURCY |first5=J. |last6=LATCHAM |first6=P. R. |title=QUERIES |journal=The Mariner's Mirror |date=January 1968 |volume=54 |issue=3 |pages=304\u2013305 |doi=10.1080/00253359.1968.10659451}}</ref> Farr was also the honorary editor of the International Lifeboat Journal between 1974 and 1983.<ref name=\"Lifeboat_48_486\">{{cite news |title=Three Lifeboat People |url=https://rnliarchive.blob.core.windows.net/media/1474/0486.pdf#page=4 |accessdate=5 November 2019 |work=The Lifeboat : Journal of the Royal National Lifeboat Institution |issue=Volume: 48 Issue: 486 |date=Autumn 1983}}</ref><ref name=\"MM70(1)\" />\n\nFarr died on 22 November 1983,<ref name=\"Lifeboat_48_486\" /> after a long struggle against deteriorating health and eyesight. His obituary in ''The Mariner\u2019s Mirror'' described him as \u2018a remarkable man, assiduous and painstaking in his research, and yet ever-ready to share his knowledge with others\u2019.<ref name=\"MM70(1)\" />\n\n==Works by Grahame Farr==\nWorks by Farr are variously catalogued under the names Grahame Edgar Farr, Grahame E. Farr, Grahame Farr, and G. E. Farr.  The following lists are largely derived from the catalogue of the [[British Library]].\n\n===''Wreck and rescue'' series, published by D. Bradford Barton, Truro===\n*''Wreck and rescue round the Cornish coast. 1. The Story of the north coast Lifeboats.'' (With Cyril Noall.) Truro, 1964.\n*''Wreck and rescue round the Cornish coast. 2. The Story of the Land's End lifeboats.'' (With Cyril Noall.) Truro, 1965.\n*''Wreck and rescue round the Cornish coast. 3. The Story of the south coast lifeboats.'' (With Cyril Noall.) Truro, 1965.\n*''Wreck and rescue in the Bristol Channel. 1. The Story of the English Lifeboats.'' Truro, 1966.\n*''Wreck and rescue in the Bristol Channel. 2. The story of the Welsh lifeboats.'' Truro, 1967.\n*''Wreck and rescue on the coast of Devon. The Story of the South Devon Lifeboats.'' Truro, 1968.\n*''Wreck and rescue on the Dorset coast. The story of the Dorset lifeboats.'' Truro, 1971.\n\n===Papers on life-boat history (self-published)===\n*No. 1: ''William Plenty's life boats, 1817-29 : and James and Edward Pellew Plenty's life boat model, 1851.'' Portishead, 1975.\n*No. 2: ''George Palmer's life-boats, 1828-47 : with allied types and variants.'' Portishead, 1975.\n*No. 3: ''Life-boats of the Shipwrecked Fishermen and Mariners' Royal Benevolent Society, 1851-4.'' Portishead, 1976.\n*No. 4: ''The tubular life-boats, 1850-1939.'' Portishead, 1977.\n*No. 5: ''The steam life-boats : with notes on earlier projects, and overseas steam life-boats.'' Portishead, 1981.\n*No. 6: ''The Lincolnshire Coast Shipwreck Association 1827-1864.'' Portishead, 1981.\n\n===Aids to life-boat history (self-published)===\n*No. 1: ''Hand-list of R.N.L.I. official numbers : and operational numbers.'' Portishead, 1978.\n*No. 2: ''British life-boat stations : a historical and geographical list.'' Portishead, 1979.\n\n===Maritime monographs and reports, published by the National Maritime Museum===\n*No. 20: ''The ship registers of the Port of Hayle, 1864-1882.'' Greenwich, 1975.\n*No. 22: ''Shipbuilding in North Devon : containing a list of the vessels known to have been built on the North Devon coast and rivers, with an introduction, notes on the builders, appendices, tables and a map.'' Greenwich, 1976.\n\n===Other Books===\n*''The Somersetshire Life-Boats. A brief history of rescue work on the Somersetshire coast.'' Bristol, 1935.\n*''[https://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/History/bristolrecordsociety/publications/brs15.pdf Records of Bristol Ships, 1800-1838. Vessels over 150 tons.]'' Bristol, 1950.\n*''Somerset Harbours, including the Port of Bristol.'' London, 1954.\n*''Chepstow Ships.'' Chepstow, 1954.\n*''West Country Passenger Steamers.'' London, 1956.\n*''The Bristol Shiplovers' Society, 1931-1956.'' Bristol, 1957.\n*''The Steamship Great Western: the first Atlantic liner.'' Bristol, 1963.\n*''The Steamship Great Britain.'' Bristol, 1965.\n*''West Country passenger steamers.'' Second edition. Prescot, 1967.\n*''Cornish shipwrecks.'' (With Cyril Noall.) Truro, 1969.\n*''Ships and Harbours of Exmoor (Microstudy).'' Dulverton, 1970.\n*''Bristol shipbuilding in the nineteenth century.'' Bristol, 1971.\n*''Ships and Harbours of Exmoor (Microstudy).'' Second edition. Dulverton, 1974.\n*''Penlee Lifeboat: History of the Penlee and Penzance Branch of the R.N.L.I.'' (With John Corin.) Penzance, 1983.\n\n==Archives==\n[[National Maritime Museum]] holds Farr's card index system for ships entering the Bristol Channel (between Milford, Gloucester and the Scilly Isles). Information in the cards \u2018include the name of the vessel (arranged in the index alphabetically); port of registry and date which includes ports UK wide; an abbreviation description of the vessel (no guide to abbreviations available); dimensions; tonnage; builders; engines; the first owners and if any changes were made to the vessel\u2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Uncatalogued: Farr, Grahame Edgar, 1912-1983, Shipping Historian: Card Index for vessels entering the Bristol Channel |url=https://collections.rmg.co.uk/archive/objects/463657.html |website=The Collection |publisher=Royal Museums Greenwich |accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Friends of [[Purton Hulks|Purton]] acquired Farr's photographic collection in 2007. Started in the 1930s, the collection consists of several thousand black and white images of local schooners, trows, lighters, coasters, paddle steamers and related subjects.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barnett |first1=Paul |title=Graham Farr photographic collection |url=http://www.cotswoldcanalsheritage.org.uk/page_id__199.aspx?path=0p2p29p |website=Cotswold Canals Heritage |publisher=Cotswold Canals Heritage |accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Webery : The Grahame Farr Photographic Collection |journal=South West Soundings : The Newsletter of the South West Maritime History Society |date=March 2010 |issue= 78 |page=27 |url=https://www.swmaritime.org.uk/_webedit/uploaded-files/All%20Files/SWS78.pdf |accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Exmoor]] Society's archives include extensive material relating to the commissioning and publication of Farr's microstudy on the \u2018\u2019Ships and Harbours of Exmoor\u2019\u2019 (Dulverton, 1970, second edition 1974).<ref>{{cite web |title=Farr's Ships and Harbours : Material relating to Farr\u2019s microstudy on the Ships and Harbours of Exmoor |url=https://www.exmoorsociety.com/content/catalogue_item/victor-bonham-carter-papers/exmoor-press-papers/farrs-ships-and-harbours |website=The Exmoor Society |publisher=The Exmoor Society |accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Farr, Grahame}}\n[[Category:British maritime historians|Farr, Grahame]]\n[[Category:1912 births|Farr, Grahame]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths|Farr, Grahame]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grahame_Farr"}
{"title_page": "David Tomlinson", "text_new": "{{short description|English actor}}\n{{Other people|David Tomlinson}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name             = David Tomlinson\n|image           = Mary Poppins4.jpg\n|caption          = Tomlinson as George Banks in ''[[Mary Poppins (film)|Mary Poppins]]'', 1964\n|birth_name     = David Cecil MacAlister Tomlinson\n|birth_date      = {{birth date|1917|05|07|df=y}}\n|birth_place     = [[Henley-on-Thames]], [[Oxfordshire]], England\n|death_date     = {{death date and age|2000|06|24|1917|05|07|df=y}}\n|death_place      = [[Westminster]], [[London]], England\n|other_names   =\n|occupation      = Actor\n|years_active     = 1940\u20131980\n|spouse            = {{marriage|Mary Lindsay Hiddingh|1943|1943|reason=her death}}<br>{{marriage|Audrey Freeman|1953|2000|reason=his death}}\n|children           = 4\n| module      = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n| allegiance    = United Kingdom\n| branch        = [[Royal Air Force]]\n| serviceyears  = 1940\u20131945\n| unit          = Film Unit\n| rank          = [[Flight Lieutenant]]\n| battles       = [[Second World War]]}}\n}}\n'''David Cecil MacAlister Tomlinson''' (7 May 1917 \u2013 24 June 2000) was an English stage, film and television actor and comedian. Having been described as both a [[leading man]] and a [[character actor]], he is primarily remembered for his roles as authority figure George Banks in [[Mary Poppins (film)|''Mary Poppins'']], fraudulent magician Professor Emelius Browne in ''[[Bedknobs and Broomsticks]]'' and as hapless antagonist Peter Thorndyke in ''[[The Love Bug]]''. Tomlinson was posthumously inducted as a [[Disney Legend]] in 2002. \n\n==Early life==\nTomlinson was born in [[Henley-on-Thames]], [[Oxfordshire]] on 7 May 1917,<ref>General Register Office of England and Wales \u2013 Birth Register for June Quarter of 1917, Henley Registration District, reference 3a 1531, listed as David C.M. Tomlinson, mother's maiden name as Sinclair-Thomson</ref> to Florence Elizabeth Tomlinson (n\u00e9e Sinclair-Thomson) (1890\u20131986) and a well-respected London solicitor father Clarence Samuel Tomlinson (1883\u20131978).<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1344949/David-Tomlinson.html |title=David Tomlinson |date=26 June 2000 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]}}</ref> He attended [[Tonbridge School]] and left to join the [[Grenadier Guards]] for 16 months.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> His father then secured him a job as a clerk at [[Shell Mex House]].\n\nHis stage career grew from amateur stage productions to his 1940 film debut in ''Quiet Wedding''. His career was interrupted when he entered [[Second World War]] service as a [[Flight Lieutenant]] in the [[Royal Air Force|RAF]]. During the war, he served as a flight instructor in [[Canada]] and appeared in three more films.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> His flying days continued after the war. On one occasion he crashed a [[De Havilland Tiger Moth|Tiger Moth]] plane near his back garden after he lost consciousness while flying.\n\n==Film career==\nDavid Tomlinson was best known for his role as George Banks, head of the Banks family, in the [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]] film ''[[Mary Poppins (film)|Mary Poppins]]'' (1964). ''Mary Poppins'' brought Tomlinson continued work with Disney, appearing in ''[[The Love Bug]]'' (1968) and ''[[Bedknobs and Broomsticks]]'' (1971). Throughout the rest of Tomlinson's film career, he never steered far from comedies. His final acting appearance was in ''[[The Fiendish Plot of Dr. Fu Manchu]]'' (1980), which was also the final film of [[Peter Sellers]]. Tomlinson retired from acting at age 63 to spend more time with his family.<ref>{{cite news |title=Whatever happened to the cast of Mary Poppins?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/06/02/whatever-happened-to-the-cast-of-mary-poppins/david-tomlinson-george-banksdespite-suffering-from-a-stammer-dav/| newspaper=The Telegraph |date=2 June 2016 |accessdate=17 February 2017}}</ref> However in 1992 at the age 75 he appeared on the Wogan show along with Tommy Cockles (Simon Day).\n\n==Personal life and death==\nTomlinson was first married to Mary Lindsay Hiddingh, daughter of L. Seton Lindsay, the vice president of the New York Life Insurance Company. She had been widowed in 1941 when her husband, Major A.G. Hiddingh, was killed in action, leaving her to care for their two young sons. Tomlinson married Mary in September 1943, but on 2 December 1943 she killed herself and her two sons in a murder-suicide by jumping from a hotel in New York City.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mother and Two Sons Plunge 15 Stories to Death in New York City| newspaper=[[Niagara Gazette|Niagara Falls Gazette]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |url=http://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%208/Niagara%20Falls%20NY%20Gazette/Niagara%20Falls%20NY%20Gazette%201943%20Nov-1944%20Feb%20Grayscale/Niagara%20Falls%20NY%20Gazette%201943%20Nov-1944%20Feb%20Grayscale%20-%200038.pdf |accessdate=15 October 2018 |date=2 December 1943}}</ref>\n\nTomlinson's second wife was actress Audrey Freeman (born 12 November 1931), whom he married on 17 May 1953, and the couple remained together for 47 years until his death. They had four sons: David Jr., William, Henry and James.<ref name='bbc'>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/804127.stm |title=Mary Poppins Star Dies |work=[[BBC News]] |date=24 June 2000}}</ref>\n\nTomlinson died peacefully in his sleep at [[King Edward VII's Hospital Sister Agnes|King Edward VII's Hospital]], Westminster, at {{nowrap|4 a.m.}} on 24 June 2000, after suffering a sudden [[stroke]].<ref>General Register Office of England and Wales \u2013 Death Register for June 2000, Westminster Registration District, reference C49C 281, listed as David Cecil Tomlinson with a date of birth of 7 May 1917.</ref><ref name='bbc'/> He was 83 years old. He was interred at his estate grounds in [[Mursley]], [[Buckinghamshire]].\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*''Garrison Follies'' (1940) (uncredited)\n*''[[Quiet Wedding]]'' (1941) as John Royd\n*''[[My Wife's Family (1941 film)|My Wife's Family]]'' (1941) as Willie Bagshott\n*''[[\"Pimpernel\" Smith]]'' (1941) as Steve\n*''Name Rank and Number'' (1941)\n*''[[The Way to the Stars]]'' (1945) as 'Prune' Parsons\n*''[[Journey Together]]'' (1945) as Smith \n*''[[I See a Dark Stranger]]'' (1946) as Intelligence Officer\n*''[[School for Secrets]]'' (1946) as Mr. Watlington\n*''[[Fame Is the Spur (film)|Fame Is the Spur]]'' (1947) as Lord Liskeard\n*''[[Master of Bankdam]]'' (1947) as Lancelot Handel Crowther\n*''[[Easy Money (1948 film)|Easy Money]]'' (1948) as Martin Latham\n*''[[Miranda (1948 film)|Miranda]]'' (1948) as Charles\n*''[[Broken Journey]]'' (1948) as Jimmy Marshall\n*''[[My Brother's Keeper (film)|My Brother's Keeper]]'' (1948) as Ronnie Waring \n*''[[Sleeping Car to Trieste]]'' (1948) as Tom Bishop\n*''[[Love in Waiting]]'' (1948) as Robert Clitheroe\n*''[[Here Come the Huggetts]]'' (1948) as Harold Hinchley\n*''[[Warning to Wantons]]'' (1949) as Count Max Kardak\n*''[[Vote for Huggett]]'' (1949) as Harold Hinchley\n*''[[Marry Me! (1949 film)|Marry Me!]]'' (1949) as David Haig\n*''[[Helter Skelter (1949 film)|Helter Skelter]]'' (1949) as Nick Martin\n*''[[The Chiltern Hundreds (film)|The Chiltern Hundreds]]'' (1949) as Lord Tony Pym\n*''[[Landfall (film)|Landfall]]'' (1949) as Binks\n*''[[So Long at the Fair]]'' (1950) as Johnny Barton\n*''[[The Wooden Horse]]'' (1950) as Philip Rowe\n*''[[Calling Bulldog Drummond]]'' (1951) as Algernon 'Algy' Longworth \n*''[[Hotel Sahara]]'' (1951) as Captain Puffin Cheyne\n*''[[The Magic Box]]'' (1951) as Assistant in Laboratory\n*''[[Castle in the Air (film)|Castle in the Air]]'' (1952) as Earl of Locharne\n*''[[Made in Heaven (1952 film)|Made in Heaven]]'' (1952) as Basil Topham\n*''[[Is Your Honeymoon Really Necessary?]]'' (1953) as Frank Betteron \n*''[[All for Mary]]'' (1955) as Humphrey 'Humpy' Miller\n*''[[Three Men in a Boat (1956 film)|Three Men in a Boat]]'' (1956) as Jerome\n*''[[Carry On Admiral]]'' (1957) as Tom Baker\n*''[[Up the Creek (1958 film)|Up the Creek]]'' (1958) as Lt. Humphrey Fairweather\n*''[[Further Up the Creek]]'' (1958) as Lt. Humphrey Fairweather\n*''[[Follow That Horse!]]'' (1960) as Dick Lanchester\n*''[[Tom Jones (1963 film)|Tom Jones]]'' (1963) as Lord Fellamar\n*''[[Mary Poppins (film)|Mary Poppins]]'' (1964) as George Banks\n*''[[The Truth About Spring]]'' (1964) as Charles Skelton\n*''[[City Under the Sea]]'' (1965) as Harold Tufnell-Jones\n*''[[The Liquidator (1965 film)|The Liquidator]]'' (1965) as Quadrant\n*''[[The Love Bug]]'' (1968) as Peter Thorndyke\n*''[[Bedknobs and Broomsticks]]'' (1971) as Professor Emilius Browne \n*''[[Bons Baisers de Hong Kong|From Hong Kong with Love]]'' (1975) as Sir John Mac Gregor\n*''[[Wombling Free]]'' (1977) as Roland Frogmorton\n*''[[The Water Babies (film)|The Water Babies]]'' (1978) as Sir John / Voice of Polar Bear\n*''[[Dominique (1978 film)|Dominique]]'' (1978) as Lawyer\n*''[[The Fiendish Plot of Dr. Fu Manchu]]'' (1980) as Sir Roger Avery (final film role)\n}}\n\n===Television===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*''The Birdcage Room'' (TV Film) (1954) - Lord Tempest \n*''All for Mary'' (Outside Broadcast of the theatre production, 1954) - Clive Norton\n*''[[Theatre Royal (TV series)|Theatre Royal]]'' (1955) - episode - The No Man - Tom Pettigo\n*''[[Theatre Night]]'' (1957) - episode - Dear Delinquent - David Warren\n*''[[ITV Play of the Week]]'' (1960) - episode - The Happy Man - Tom Swinley\n*''[[Comedy Playhouse]]'' (1967) - episode - Loitering With Intent - Charles Pinfold\n*''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]'' (1976) - episode - Nine Dragons - Blake\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*''[[The Life I Lead (play)|The Life I Lead]]'', a 2019 one-man comedy play by James Kettle which explores Tomlinson's life, starring [[Miles Jupp]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Luckier Than Most'', Tomlinson's autobiography, published in 1990.\n\n==External links==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|David_Tomlinson.ogg|2019-9-17}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n{{commons}}\n\n*{{IMDb name|0866835}}\n*{{Find a Grave|20257}}\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/804127.stm Mary Poppins Star Dies] \u2013 [[BBC]] News obituary from 2000\n*[https://d23.com/david-tomlinson/ David Tomlinson at the Disney Legends website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tomlinson, David}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Grenadier Guards soldiers]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Kent]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:People from Henley-on-Thames]]\n[[Category:People educated at Tonbridge School]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force pilots of World War II]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English actor}}\n{{Other people|David Tomlinson}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name             = David Tomlinson\n|image           = Mary Poppins4.jpg\n|caption          = Tomlinson as George Banks in ''[[Mary Poppins (film)|Mary Poppins]]'', 1964\n|birth_name     = David Cecil MacAlister Tomlinson\n|birth_date      = {{birth date|1917|05|07|df=y}}\n|birth_place     = [[Henley-on-Thames]], [[Oxfordshire]], England\n|death_date     = {{death date and age|2000|06|24|1917|05|07|df=y}}\n|death_place      = [[Westminster]], [[London]], England\n|other_names   =\n|occupation      = Actor\n|years_active     = 1940\u20131980\n|spouse            = {{marriage|Mary Lindsay Hiddingh|1943|1943|reason=her death}}<br>{{marriage|Audrey Freeman|1953|2000|reason=his death}}\n|children           = 4\n| module      = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n| allegiance    = United Kingdom\n| branch        = [[Royal Air Force]]\n| serviceyears  = 1940\u20131945\n| unit          = Film Unit\n| rank          = [[Flight Lieutenant]]\n| battles       = [[Second World War]]}}\n}}\n'''David Cecil MacAlister Tomlinson''' (7 May 1917 \u2013 24 June 2000) was an English stage, film and television actor and comedian. Having been described as both a [[leading man]] and a [[character actor]], he is primarily remembered for his roles as authority figure George Banks in [[Mary Poppins (film)|''Mary Poppins'']], fraudulent magician Professor Emelius Browne in ''[[Bedknobs and Broomsticks]]'' and as hapless antagonist Peter Thorndyke in ''[[The Love Bug]]''. Tomlinson was posthumously inducted as a [[Disney Legend]] in 2002. \n\n==Early life==\nTomlinson was born in [[Henley-on-Thames]], [[Oxfordshire]] on 7 May 1917,<ref>General Register Office of England and Wales \u2013 Birth Register for June Quarter of 1917, Henley Registration District, reference 3a 1531, listed as David C.M. Tomlinson, mother's maiden name as Sinclair-Thomson</ref> to Florence Elizabeth Tomlinson (n\u00e9e Sinclair-Thomson) (1890\u20131986) and a well-respected London solicitor father Clarence Samuel Tomlinson (1883\u20131978).<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1344949/David-Tomlinson.html |title=David Tomlinson |date=26 June 2000 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]}}</ref> He attended [[Tonbridge School]] and left to join the [[Grenadier Guards]] for 16 months.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> His father then secured him a job as a clerk at [[Shell Mex House]].\n\nHis stage career grew from amateur stage productions to his 1940 film debut in ''Quiet Wedding''. His career was interrupted when he entered [[Second World War]] service as a [[Flight Lieutenant]] in the [[Royal Air Force|RAF]]. During the war, he served as a flight instructor in [[Canada]] and appeared in three more films.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> His flying days continued after the war. On one occasion he crashed a [[De Havilland Tiger Moth|Tiger Moth]] plane near his back garden after he lost consciousness while flying.\n\n==Film career==\nDavid Tomlinson was best known for his role as George Banks, head of the Banks family, in the [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]] film ''[[Mary Poppins (film)|Mary Poppins]]'' (1964). ''Mary Poppins'' brought Tomlinson continued work with Disney, appearing in ''[[The Love Bug]]'' (1968) and ''[[Bedknobs and Broomsticks]]'' (1971). Throughout the rest of Tomlinson's film career, he never steered far from comedies. His final acting appearance was in ''[[The Fiendish Plot of Dr. Fu Manchu]]'' (1980), which was also the final film of [[Peter Sellers]]. Tomlinson retired from acting at age 63 to spend more time with his family.<ref>{{cite news |title=Whatever happened to the cast of Mary Poppins?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/06/02/whatever-happened-to-the-cast-of-mary-poppins/david-tomlinson-george-banksdespite-suffering-from-a-stammer-dav/| newspaper=The Telegraph |date=2 June 2016 |accessdate=17 February 2017}}</ref> However in 1992 at the age 75 he appeared on the Wogan show along with Tommy Cockles (Simon Day).\n\n==Personal life and death==\nTomlinson was first married to Mary Lindsay Hiddingh, daughter of L. Seton Lindsay, the vice president of the New York Life Insurance Company. She had been widowed in 1941 when her husband, Major A.G. Hiddingh, was killed in action, leaving her to care for their two young sons. Tomlinson married Mary in September 1943, but on 2 December 1943 she killed herself and her two sons in a murder-suicide by jumping from a hotel in New York City.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mother and Two Sons Plunge 15 Stories to Death in New York City| newspaper=[[Niagara Gazette|Niagara Falls Gazette]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |url=http://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%208/Niagara%20Falls%20NY%20Gazette/Niagara%20Falls%20NY%20Gazette%201943%20Nov-1944%20Feb%20Grayscale/Niagara%20Falls%20NY%20Gazette%201943%20Nov-1944%20Feb%20Grayscale%20-%200038.pdf |accessdate=15 October 2018 |date=2 December 1943}}</ref>\n\nTomlinson's second wife was actress Audrey Freeman (born 12 November 1931), whom he married on 17 May 1953, and the couple remained together for 47 years until his death. They had four sons: David Jr., William, Henry and James.<ref name='bbc'>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/804127.stm |title=Mary Poppins Star Dies |work=[[BBC News]] |date=24 June 2000}}</ref>\n\nTomlinson died peacefully in his sleep at [[King Edward VII's Hospital Sister Agnes|King Edward VII's Hospital]], Westminster, at {{nowrap|4 a.m.}} on 24 June 2000, after suffering a sudden [[stroke]].<ref>General Register Office of England and Wales \u2013 Death Register for June 2000, Westminster Registration District, reference C49C 281, listed as David Cecil Tomlinson with a date of birth of 7 May 1917.</ref><ref name='bbc'/> He was 83 years old. He was interred at his estate grounds in [[Mursley]], [[Buckinghamshire]].\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*''Garrison Follies'' (1940) (uncredited)\n*''[[Quiet Wedding]]'' (1941) as John Royd\n*''[[My Wife's Family (1941 film)|My Wife's Family]]'' (1941) as Willie Bagshott\n*''[[\"Pimpernel\" Smith]]'' (1941) as Steve\n*''Name Rank and Number'' (1941)\n*''[[The Way to the Stars]]'' (1945) as 'Prune' Parsons\n*''[[Journey Together]]'' (1945) as Smith \n*''[[I See a Dark Stranger]]'' (1946) as Intelligence Officer\n*''[[School for Secrets]]'' (1946) as Mr. Watlington\n*''[[Fame Is the Spur (film)|Fame Is the Spur]]'' (1947) as Lord Liskeard\n*''[[Master of Bankdam]]'' (1947) as Lancelot Handel Crowther\n*''[[Easy Money (1948 film)|Easy Money]]'' (1948) as Martin Latham\n*''[[Miranda (1948 film)|Miranda]]'' (1948) as Charles\n*''[[Broken Journey]]'' (1948) as Jimmy Marshall\n*''[[My Brother's Keeper (film)|My Brother's Keeper]]'' (1948) a