men artists from Kerala]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Malayalam cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Tamil cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards South winners]]\n[[Category:Kerala State Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Thiruvananthapuram]]\n[[Category:Tamil Nadu State Film Awards winners]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Child actresses in Malayalam cinema]]\n[[Category:Indian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Malayalam television]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Kannada television]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian actress}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2013}}\n{{tone|date=May 2015}}\n}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name              = Kavitha Ranjini\n|image             = \n|other names       = Urvashi/Kavitha Manoranjini/Oorvasi/Urvasi/Oorvashi\n|birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1970|01|25}}<ref>https://www.filmibeat.com/celebs/urvashi.html</ref>\n|birth_place       = [[Thiruvananthapuram]], [[Kerala]], India\n|parents           = Chavara V. P. Nair<br>Vijayalakshmi\n|family            = [[Kalaranjini]] (sister)<br/>[[Kalpana (Malayalam actress)|Kalpana]] (sister)<br/>Kamal Roy (brother)<br/>Prince (brother)<br>[[Sooranad Kunjan Pillai]] (grandfather)\n|birthname         = Kavitha Ranjini\n|spouse            = [[Manoj K. Jayan]] (2000\u20132008)<br/>(Divorced)<br/>Shivaprasad (2013\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web |author=IST |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/articles/546033/20140401/actress-urvashi-marries-again-wedlock-urvasi-malayalam,sckwrlekra.htm |title=Popular Actress Urvashi Enters into Wedlock Again |publisher=Ibtimes.co.in |date=2014-04-01 |accessdate=2018-03-09}}</ref>\n|children  = Tejalakshmi (b.2001)<br/>Ishaan Prajapathi (b.2014) \n}}\n'''Kavitha Ranjini''', known by the stage name '''Urvashi''' (born 25 January 1970) is an Indian film actress, television host and producer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mathrubhumi.com/movies/interview/114588/ |title=\u0d28\u0d3e\u0d2f\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d \u0d0e\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d4d \u0d2d\u0d2f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d23\u0d02?, Interview - Mathrubhumi Movies |publisher=Mathrubhumi.com |date=2010-07-21 |accessdate=2014-08-13}}</ref>\n\nUrvashi was a prominent [[lead actress]] of the 1980s and 1990s, primarily in [[Malayalam film|Malayalam]] and [[Tamil film]]s. She has written the films ''[[Ulsavamelam]]'' and ''[[Pidakkozhi Koovunna Noottandu]]'', the latter was also produced by her. She won the [[National Film Award for Best Supporting Actress]] for her performance in ''[[Achuvinte Amma]]'' (2005).<ref name=\"mathrubhumi1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mathrubhumi.com/mb4eves/online/malayalam/kerala/women/articles/infocus_interview-article-90671 |title=\u0d0f\u0d15\u0d3e\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d24\u0d2f\u0d41\u0d1f\u0d46 \u0d15\u0d1f\u0d32\u0d4d\u200d \u0d1e\u0d3e\u0d28\u0d4d\u200d \u0d28\u0d40\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d1f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d41\u0d02 - articles,infocus_interview - Mathrubhumi Eves |publisher=Mathrubhumi.com |accessdate=2014-08-13}}</ref> She has won the [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actress]] a record five times, which includes three consecutive wins from 1989 to 1991. She has also won two [[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]].\n\n==Personal life==\nUrvashi was born on 25 January 1969, at [[Thiruvananthapuram]], Kerala to actor Chavara V. P. Nair and Vijayalakshmi. Her elder sisters are actresses [[Kalaranjini]] and [[Kalpana (Malayalam actress)|Kalpana]]. Her two brothers, Kamal Roy and late Prince had also acted in few Malayalam movies. Prince (Nandu of [[Layanam]] fame) committed suicide at the age of 26.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2009/03/20/stories/2009032050740100.htm |title=Friday Review uh kkk ch jo khelz must c free urdu \\ spam p shav KFC : The Urvashi formula |work=The Hindu |date=2009-03-20 |accessdate=2018-03-09}}</ref> She had her primary education from Fort Girl's Mission High School, Thiruvananthapuram, until fourth grade and later at Corporation Higher Secondary School, Kodambakkam until ninth grade, when the family shifted to [[Chennai]]. She couldn't continue her studies since she had become busy with her movie career by then.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lifeglint.com/content/emigre/140324/uravashi-and-munthanai-mudichu |title=\u0d2e\u0d41\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3e\u0d23\u0d46 \u0d2e\u0d41\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d1a\u0d4d\u0d1a\u0d41\u0d02 \u0d2a\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d3e\u0d32\u0d41\u0d15\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d3f \u0d15\u0d35\u0d3f\u0d24\u0d2f\u0d41\u0d02 |language=ta |author=PK Sreenivasan |accessdate=2018-03-09}}</ref> Firstly, Urvashi was acting in three films, Bhagyaraj saw the rush and booked her in ''Munthanai Mudichi''. Those three directors helped Urvashi to get preference in ''Munthanai Mudichi'' call-sheets. They calculated that the film would become a hit, then they could release their films with much profit.\n\nUrvashi married film actor Manoj K. Jayan on 11 October 2000. They have a daughter Tejalakshmi, born in 2001. After divorce from her first husband Manoj K. Jayan in 2008, Urvashi married [[Chennai]] based builder Sivaprasad in November 2013. The couple had a boy on August 2014, named Ishaan Prajapathi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vinodadarshan.com/2014/03/actress-urvashi-second-marriage-with.html |title=Actress Urvashi's Second Marriage with Sivaprasad |date=2014-03-30 |accessdate=2018-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\nShe acted in around 500 films in Malayalam, Tamil, Telugu, Kannada and Hindi. She started her acting career as a child artist, at the age of 8, in a Malayalam movie ''[[Vidarunna Mottukal]]'', released in 1977, her sister Kalpana also debuted in the same movie. She then acted in ''Kathirmandapam'', released in 1979, as [[Jayabharathi]]'s daughter. She acted as [[Srividya]]'s dance student in the movie ''Digvijayam'', released in 1980, she plays [[Krishna]] in the song sequence ''Madhumaasa Nikunjathil'', where her sister [[Kalpana (Malayalam actress)|Kalpana]] plays the role of [[Radha]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Cinemaa Chirimaa with Kalpana and Manju Pilla: 22-9-2014 |url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x26f7br_cinemaa-chirimaa-22-9-2014-22-september-2014-part-2-mazhavil-manorama_tv?start=220 |publisher=mazhavilmanorama |accessdate=2018-03-09}}</ref> She has also acted as a child artist in ''Ninaivukal Maraivathillai'', a Tamil movie, in 1983, but it was never released. Then she acted as a heroine, at the age of 13, to [[Karthik (actor)|Karthik]] in the movie ''Thodarum Uravu'', which completed shooting in 1983, but released in 1986.<ref name=mathrubhumi1/>\n\nHer first released film as heroine was ''Munthanai Mudichchu'' ([[Tamil cinema|Tamil]], directed by [[K. Bhagyaraj]]) in 1983, making her debut movie. ''Ethirppukal'' ([[Malayalam]], 1984) was one of her earlier films in [[Malayalam]]. During the peak of her career, she starred in M. P. Sukumaran Nair's award-winning film ''Kazhakam'' in 1995, without taking a single penny as remuneration. She was awarded Best Actress for this role. She has acted in some advertisements, and has participated in many stage shows also.\n\nShe has acted in successful movies in Kannada such as ''Shravana Bantu'', ''E Jeeva Ninagagi'', ''Nanu Nanna Hendti'' and ''Rama Shama Bhama'' and she became one of the best actresses in Kannada cinema, She has acted with Dr. Rajkumar, Ravichandran, Vishnuvardhan, Kamal Haasan and Ramesh Arvind in Kannada.\n\nUrvashi is an actress who has performed multifaceted roles in her career. She is considered as an acting encyclopedia. Her dialogue delivery, subtlety and fine nuances, handling of characters with great poise and ease and above all the natural feel is commendable. No other actresses must have performed the number of characters as she has. Whether it is from her first film until her latest most successful film ''Ente Ummante Peru'', the naturalness of her acting brings tears to the audience. There is so much to learn and understand from the characters which she performed. Even dubbing artists also have mentioned that doing dubbing for Urvashi is the most challenging and exciting one where you get so much to learn.{{cn|reason=looks like original 'research'|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Awards==\n'''[[National Film Awards]]'''\n*2006: [[National Film Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] - ''[[Achuvinte Amma]]''\n\n;''[[Kerala State Film Awards]]''\n*1989: [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actress]] - ''[[Mazhavil Kavadi]]'', ''[[Varthamanakalam]]''\n*1990: [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actress]] - ''[[Thalayanamanthram]]''\n*1991: [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actress]] - ''[[Bharatham]]'', ''[[Mukha Chithram]]'', ''[[Kakkathollayiram]]'', ''[[Kadinjool Kalyanam]]''\n*1995: [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actress]] - ''[[Kazhakam]]''\n*2006: [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actress]] - ''[[Madhuchandralekha]]''\n\n;'''[[Filmfare Awards South]]'''\n*2010: [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actress - Malayalam]] - ''[[Mummy & Me]]''\n*2018: Nominated - [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Tamil]] - ''[[Magalir Mattum]]''\n\n;'''[[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]]'''\n*1994: [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award Special Prize]] -  ''[[Magalir Mattum]]''\n*1995: [[Tamil Nadu State Film Honorary Award|Kalaivanar Award]] for Best Actress by Tamil Nadu Government\n\n; [[Kerala Film Critics Association Awards]]\n*1990: Best Actress - ''[[Thalayanamanthram]]'' \n*1989: Best Actress - ''[[Varthamanakalam]]''\n\n;[[Vanitha Film Awards]]\n*2019: Best Actress-Special Performance- ''[[Aravindante Athidhikal]], [[Ente Ummante Peru]]''\n\n;[[Asianet Film Awards]]\n*2019: Best Actress-Special Jury Award- ''[[Aravindante Athidhikal]], [[